<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GrenadaRetrospective     10-23 1146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grenada Retrospective,1175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>What Drove The U.S. Into Grenada: The Debate Isn't Over</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan likes to boast that Marxists
have not gained a ``single square inch'' of territory during his
tenure, and one of his more satisfying moments occurred when a
communist government actually was uprooted.
   Rolling back communism was once an American cold war battle cry
but Marxist regimes always proved remarkably resilient. In the
post-World War II era, the trend was constant: When Marxists took
power, they were there to stay.
   Five years ago that pattern was interrupted. On Oct. 25, 1983,
U.S. troops, aided by forces from seven friendly Caribbean
countries, deposed the leftist government in Grenada.
   Was the administration telling the truth when it said the
invasion was justified by dangers confronting the more than 700
American medical students on the island? Or was that just an excuse
for striking a blow against a country simply because it had ties to
the Soviet bloc?
   Was Grenada an event of transcendental importance or merely a
speck on the historical horizon? Did the Soviets see Grenada, with
its deep water port, as an ideal stopping off place for nuclear
missile submarines?
   To Michael Ledeen, a former administration aide who spent months
studying official documents captured on Grenada by U.S. military
forces, the events of October 1983 had an ``enormous impact''
psychologically.
   ``It may well be that 20 years from now, people will say that
was the beginning of the end of the Soviet empire,'' Ledeen said.
   ``The Russians had always claimed that once a country became
part of communist world, it was there to stay. Grenada proved that
it wasn't.''
   But former National Security Council aide Oliver L. North felt
that Grenada could not be regarded as a major defeat for
international communism because the government there was ousted by
foreign invaders, not by a popular uprising.
   Assistant Secretary of State Langhorne A. Motley who, like
North, played a key behind-the scenes role in coordinating the
invasion, said the episode sent a clear message to America's
friends and adversaries.
   ``It showed that the United States was prepared to use force in
the defense of its national interests,'' said Motley, who left
government service in 1985.
   Motley insisted that the driving force behind the invasion was
concern for the fate of the American medical students on the island
after leftist opponents of Prime Minister Maurice Bishop deposed
and then executed him and about 50 of his supporters on the
bloodiest day in Grenada's history.
   Afterward, the revolutionary military council which ousted
Bishop imposed a 24-hour curfew. Motley noted there was no official
U.S. presence on the island and said State Department efforts to
obtain information about the students were unsuccessful.
   He and other officials were haunted by the memory of the 52
American hostages who had been detained by Iranian militants for
444 days. As Motley described it, alarm at the State Department
mounted as the days passed with no word on whether the students
were safe.
   He ridiculed the notion that the prime U.S. concern in going
ahead with the invasion was the existence of a pro-Soviet
government in Grenada.
   ``The primary and overwhelming consideration was the safety of
the students,'' he said.
   But Cuban President Fidel Castro has said the administration
fabricated a ``mountain of lies'' about the supposed dangers
confronting the students. He felt the administration was guided
above all by aggressive intentions.
   Ramon Sanchez Parodi, head of Cuba's diplomatic mission in
Washington, said the stated U.S. concern about the students was a
``very thin veil'' covering the Reagan administration's true intent.
   ``There was no effort of a non-military nature to take the
students out,'' Sanchez Parodi said. The United States, he said,
had no purpose other than to ``impose its will'' on the people of
Grenada. In the aftermath, Cuba moved quickly to bolster its own
self-defense, worried that it might be the next American target.
   Answering critics, Reagan noted that the U.S. intervention was
carried out at the request of the Organization of Eastern Caribbean
States, which was worried about Grenada being used as a base of
subversion against Caribbean democracies. Some had security forces
totaling only a few dozen compared with Grenada's force of 4,000.
   When the Reagan administration took office in 1981, it found the
trends in the Caribbean area worrisome. Leftist governments had
assumed power over the previous two years in Grenada, Nicaragua and
Suriname.
   In Grenada, Bishop's government moved quickly to establish close
ties with Cuba. A large contingent of Cubans began constructing an
airport capable of handling Cuba's large fleet of MiG jet fighters.
   Although Bishop insisted that the airport was designed for
commercial purposes, U.S. military analysts were concerned that the
facility had the potential for enabling Cuba to project its
military power for the first time into the northern tier of South
America. Captured documents showed that Grenada had entered into
three military agreements with the Soviet Union and one each with
Cuba and North Korea _ all secret.
   Whatever the objectives of the Soviet bloc in Grenada might have
been, the ouster of a friendly government there and its replacement
by an avowedly pro-American regime was a setback, especially for
Castro.
   Cuba had committed substantial resources in Grenada for more
than four years and Castro had nothing to show for it. The 25th
anniversary of his own revolution, which occurred nine weeks after
the Grenada invasion, was a low key affair instead of the big
extravaganza he had planned.
   The invasion also produced shock waves in Nicaragua and
Suriname. In Managua, Defense Minister Humberto Ortega was
determined not to allow the United States to use the same pretext
for invading Nicaragua as it did in Grenada.
   He called U.S. Ambassador Anthony Quainton and offered him
unlimited use of Nicaragua's bus fleet to evacuate Americans from
the country. In Suriname, military leader Desi Bouterse, worried
that the large and growing Cuban presence in his country might be
seen as a provocation by the United States, ordered the Cubans home.
   Delighted that the invasion seemed to make America's adversaries
in the hemisphere squirm, one official facetiously said at the time
that the best way to deal with Nicaragua was to set up a medical
school for Americans in the country.
   The invasion, of course, was not cost-free. Eighteen Americans,
45 Grenadans and 29 Cubans were killed during the fighting.
   But given the fact that the students were spared potential harm
and the Soviet bloc had lost an ally in the process, the
administration felt the loss of life was worth it.
   The episode helped ease the anguish of what was perhaps the
darkest moment of the Reagan presidency: the deaths of 241 U.S.
Marines in a bombing incident in Lebanon just two days before the
Grenada invasion.
</TEXT>
