<1ST_LINE>u i AM-LastTemptation-Fire     10-23 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Last Temptation-Fire,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10 Injured In Fire At Theatre Showing `Last Temptation of Christ'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire that started in a theater seat heavily damaged
a Left Bank cinema showing ``The Last Temptation of Christ''
Saturday night and injured 10 people, one seriously, police said.
   The fire began about 11 p.m. (6 p.m. EDT) at the St. Michel
cinema, a two-theatre building that for two weeks was the scene of
religious protests against the controversial film by American
director Martin Scorsese.
   The blaze began at a seat in the theatre adjacent to the one
showing ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' at the time the audience
was leaving the Scorsese film, according to fire officials who
spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping with departmental policy.
   A theatre employee, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
written threats had been received by the cinema.
   Firemen extinguished the blaze an hour later, but officials said
the building suffered serious damage. Theatre manager Gerard Pascal
said the entrance to the theatre looked like it had been bombed. No
precise damage estimate was immediately available.
   The blaze was under investigation by the criminal brigade of the
city police department, indicating arson was suspected.
   ``The flames quickly reached a height of nearly two meters (6.5
feet) and then spread to the stairs where people were leaving the
other theatre,'' said one spectator who declined to give his name.
   Most of those attending the Scorsese film had left and only
about 18 people remained in the theatre when the blaze began, the
news agency Agence France-Presse reported.
   One seriously injured spectator and was taken to Fernand Widal
Hospital, said Raoul Viger, a fire department spokesman. No further
details on his condition were immediately available.
   Two women and a man, who came to the aid of spectators before
firefighters arrived, were taken to Cochin Hospital suffering from
smoke inhalation. Six policemen were also injured, Vigir said.
   About 100 firefighters in 11 trucks filled the Place St. Michel,
a well-known Left Bank square popular with students, and blocked
the street running beside the Seine River while the fire was
brought under control.
   The film, an adaptation of the 1955 Nikos Kazanthakis novel,
sparked demonstrations by Christian groups when it was released in
the United States and Europe.
   Some Christians have been offended by the film's portrayal of
Jesus Christ as a human being with passions and weaknesses rather
than a divine creature. The film includes a scene in which Christ
imagines having sex with the prostitute Mary Magdalene.
</TEXT>
