<1ST_LINE>u i AM-HurricaneJoan 5thLd-Writethru   10-23 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Joan, 5th Ld-Writethru,a0675,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hurricane Slams Into Central America, Storm's Death Toll at 70</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with five more dead in
Nicaragua, 300,000 homeless, flooding and evacuations around
Managua, midnight storm reading. Pickup 10th graf pvs `Twenty-one
people...'; SUBS final 2 grafs `At 9...center said.' with 2 grafs
to UPDATE with midnight readings.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Joan tore across Nicaragua
Saturday with 125 mph winds and torrential rains, setting off
floods and mud slides before turning into a tropical storm. In less
than a week, Joan killed at least 70 people and left hundreds of
thousands homeless.
   Lights were cut off across Managua as the storm lashed the
capital. The Voice of Nicaragua radio reported evacuations and
flooding in a wide area around the city; roads were cut and several
people were injured when tree limbs fell across their houses.
   ``We had to look for shelter to save our lives,'' said Xiomara
Campo, sitting on the floor of a church shelter in Rama, about 150
miles east of Managua.
   At midnight Saturday Joan's winds were 40 mph, tropical storm
strength. Hurricane warnings were discontinued but flash flood and
mud slide warnings continued for Costa Rica, Nicaragua and Honduras.
   At least 20 people were reported killed in Nicaragua on
Saturday, 21 in Costa Rica and three in Panama, raising the overall
death toll from the storm in Central and South America since Monday
to 70. In Nicaragua, 140 people were reported missing.
   About 300,000 were left homeless, hundreds were injured and more
than 80,000 were evacuated in the three Central American countries.
   At 4 a.m. Saturday, the eye of the hurricane crossed the
Atlantic coast at Bluefields in Nicaragua, a city surrounded by
mangrove swamps and low-lying jungle about 180 miles east of
Managua.
   Nicaraguan radio reported 15 dead in Bluefields and 90 percent
of the homes in the city were destroyed. Two deaths were reported
north of the city and three deaths and dozens of injuries were
reported on Great Corn Island off eastern Nicaragua.
   Twenty-one people were killed in neighboring Costa Rica and 15
were missing, authorities said. Officials in Panama reported three
deaths and said the Pan-American Highway was closed by mud slides.
   The hurricane, which killed 26 people last week in Colombia and
Venezuela, lurked off the coast for days, giving Central America
time to prepare for the blow.
   Nicaraguan radio reports said officials issued an urgent request
for hospital tents, medicine and clothing. The Bluefields airport
was being inspected to see if Cuban planes could land with relief
supplies, according to the reports.
   President Daniel Ortega said authorities had no idea about the
total number of casualties.
   ``The destruction was total,'' said Ray Hooker, a national
legislator who spoke via government radio from Corn Island. ``There
is not one house with a roof.''
   Hooker said trees, churches, schools, the island's only clinic
and its docks and shrimp processing plant were damaged. He said the
island had one doctor to treat dozens of injuries.
   In Costa Rica, some houses were under water and their
inhabitants were evacuated by boat, said Victor Brenes of the
National Emergency Committee.
   About 8,000 people live on Corn Island and 60,000 in the
Bluefields area. Thousands were evacuated, but Ortega said
thousands more who were unaccustomed to hurricanes ignored warnings
to leave.
   The last hurricane to hit Nicaragua was in 1911. Costa Rica has
never been hit by a hurricane in recorded history.
   ``This is the worst natural phenomenon since the earthquake of
Dec. 23, 1972,'' said an announcer on Nicaragua's government-run
radio network. More than 10,000 people perished in the quake, which
destroyed most of the capital.
   Ortega said Nicaraguan rebels known as Contras attacked an
ambulance during the storm in south-central Nicaragua, wounding the
driver and a child.
   Barricada, the newspaper of Nicaragua's ruling Sandinista party,
said that 20,000 people had been evacuated from one low-lying area
of Managua, but visits by Associated Press reporters Saturday found
little evidence of evacuations on that scale.
   The hurricane hit along the Miskito Coast, an isolated area
whose sparse population is largely English-speaking Indians and
blacks. No main roads connect Bluefields to the rest of the nation.
   At midnight EDT the center of the storm was just outside Managua
at latitude 12.0 north and longitude 86.0 west, according to the
U.S. National Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, Fla.
   The storm was expected to continue moving across Nicaragua at
about 9 mph. Rain over 15 inches was likely over Costa Rica,
Nicaragua and parts of Honduras, the hurricane center said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
