<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 0138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-BridgeOlympiad     10-23 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bridge Olympiad,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United States Wins Championship For First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States won the championship of
the World Contract Bridge Team Olympiad for the first time ever
Saturday, defeating Austria 289-247 in the 96-deal final.
   The United States has won every other world title at least once,
and it now holds the championship in every world event except the
Women's Olympiad.
   Seymon Deutsch of San Antonio, Texas, was the only member of the
team who had never won a world championship.
   ``It's fantastic, it's unreal,'' he said. ``It's the thrill of a
lifetime.''
   Bobby Wolff of Dallas was worried when he finished play.
   ``They played absolutely perfect bridge against us over the
final 16 deals, and I thought we were 2-1 to lose. What a relief to
discover that our teammates did so well.''
   Wolff won the Bermuda Bowl in 1970, 1971, 1977, 1983, 1985 and
1987. Another member of the U.S. team in Venice, Bob Hamman of
Dallas, was his teammate in all those victories. As a partnership,
Wolff and Hamman won the 1974 World Open Pairs. Wolff has also won
the World Mixed Teams.
   Jim Jacoby of Richardson, Texas, also was on the championship
Bermuda Bowl teams in 1970 and 1971. The Olympiad in Venice was his
third world championship.
   Eric Rodwell of Lafayette, Ind., and Jeff Meckstroth of
Columbus, Ohio, were on the team that won the Bermuda Bowl in 1981
and they were runaway victors in the World Open Pairs in 1986.
   Saturday's victory marked the third time Dan Morse, the
non-playing captain, had led teams to victory.
   Playing for Austria in the final were Heinrich Berger, Jan
Fucik, Alfred Kadlek, Friedrich Kubac, Wolfgang Meinl and Franz
Terraneo, with Franz Baratta as the non-playing captain.
   In the Women's Olympiad, Denmark defeated Britain 178-157 in a
64-deal match that concluded Friday.
</TEXT>
