<2ND_LINE>BC-Hirohito,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor's Blood Pressure Sharply Rises; Eric Clapton Insures His
Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito was in good spirits Sunday, but
palace officials said his blood pressure rose to its highest level
since he was confined to bed with internal bleeding five weeks ago.
   The 87-year-old monarch's blood pressure at mid-afternoon was
174 over 76, Imperial Household Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda said.
The reading was sharply higher than in the morning, when it was 160
over 70. A normal reading is about 120 over 80.
   High blood pressure places an additional burden on the heart and
other organs and can aggravate internal bleeding.
   Maeda said Hirohito continued to discharge small amounts of
blood from his bowels Saturday and Sunday but remained in good
spirits and was chatting amiably with aides and family members.
   Maeda said earlier that the emperor's serious anemia improved
slightly after large blood transfusions. Hirohito received 24.8
pints of blood since his condition worsened, nearly three times the
normal amount in his body.
   In a related development, British rock guitarist Eric Clapton
reportedly took out a $105,000 insurance policy against
cancellation of his concert tour next month in Japan if Hirohito
dies. The Sun newspaper of London said the policy would pay Clapton
more than $1.75 million.
   Already, many concerts, festivals and other events have been
canceled in Japan because of the emperor's illness.
</TEXT>
