<1ST_LINE>r i BC-TyphoonRuby     10-23 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Typhoon Ruby,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Kills 10, Leaves 20,000 Homeless In Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAGAYAN DE ORO, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Ruby dumped heavy
rains and triggered flash floods Sunday in the southern
Philippines, leaving 20,000 homeless, officials said. Two people
drowned and eight others were feared dead.
   At 4:30 p.m. (4:30 a.m. EDT), Ruby was estimated to be about 60
miles southeast of the coastal town of Borongan on Samar island,
about 360 miles southeast of the capital Manila, the Manila weather
bureau said.
   Ruby, centered over the Philippine Sea, had sustained winds of
75 miles per hour and was moving northwest at 15 mph toward
Borongan, said forecaster Pedro Deogracias.
   Deogracias said at that course Ruby will hit Borongan by Monday
morning.
   Col. Triumfo Agustin, Philippine Constabulary regional
commander, said Ruby caused flash floods in the six villages on the
outskirts of Cagayan de Oro in Misamis Oriental province, about 500
miles south of Manila.
   Agustin said 1,000 houses along the bloated Agusan River were
destroyed, leaving at least 20,000 people homeless. He added that
10 people were reportedly carried by the strong current and feared
dead, but only two bodies have so far been recovered.
   The typhoon also destroyed the Agusan bridge, Agustin said.
   A check with relief agencies in Manila could not immediately
confirm the report. Typhoon reports usually take days before
reaching the capital.
   ``We have advised the remaining residents along the river to
seek higher ground,'' Agustin said.
   Manoling Abejuela, Cagayan de Oro's planning engineer, estimated
damage to agricultural crops and houses at $2.4 million dollars.
</TEXT>
