<HEAD>Israeli Troops and Christian Militiamen Reportedly Battle
Guerrillas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with four guerrillas reported killed.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HASBAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops and allied Christian
militiamen of the South Lebanon Army clashed with guerrillas in the
foothills of Mount Hermon Sunday, police said. Beirut radio
stations reported four guerrillas were killed.
   The sound of machine-gun fire and rocket-propelled grenades
reverberated across the slopes of the mountain, on the northern
edge of Israel's self-designated security zone in south Lebanon.
   ``The battle has been raging since first light,'' said a police
spokesman in Hasbaya at midmorning, after four hours of fighting.
   Hasbaya overlooks the border enclave controlled by Israeli
troops and the predominantly Christian militiamen of the South
Lebanon Army, or SLA.
   ``We haven't any solid information yet, but it seems the
Israelis and the SLA have intercepted a guerrilla party trying to
infiltrate into their zone,'' said the spokesman, who cannot be
named under standing regulations.
   He said he could not tell whether the guerrillas involved in the
battle were Palestinians or Iranian-backed Shiite Moslems from the
fundamentalist Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   The Voice of Lebanon and Voice of Free Lebanon, both
Christian-controlled, cited unidentified informed sources as saying
four guerrillas died but did not further identify the casualties.
   The Israeli air force blasted Palestinian and Shiite bases in
south Lebanon Friday, killing 21 people and wounding 34, in
apparent revenge for a suicide car bomb attack in the security zone
on Wednesday.
   Seven Israeli soldiers were killed and eight others and two
Lebanese women wounded in the car bombing.
   Israel maintains a six-to-10-mile-wide zone in south Lebanon to
guard against possible attacks by guerrillas in Lebanon on areas in
northern Israel.
