<DOCNO> AP881023-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-100thCongress-Contras Bjt   10-23 0959</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-100th Congress-Contras, Bjt,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Without Reagan, Fate of Contras Appears Dim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Contras, the Nicaraguan rebels President
Reagan lauded as ``freedom fighters'' and made the centerpiece of
his Central America policy, are fading into history.
   Supporters and opponents alike say the rebels, who once claimed
to be inflicting severe damage on the leftist Sandinista regime
through their forays inside Nicaragua, now are little more than
refugees huddled in camps along the Honduran border.
   ``Every single Contra who died, died for nothing, it turns
out,'' said Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., who has led a losing
battle in the House of Representatives to win military aid for the
rebels. ``I've got to say that I'm depressed about it. I would like
to find a way to put a good light on it, but I can't.''
   Reagan's personal devotion to the Contras has largely sustained
them since they were formed in 1981. Congress, alternately going
along and resisting aid to the rebels, sent at least $294 million
to support the Contras over that period. That doesn't include some
$41 million raised from other countries and private contributors,
or illegally diverted during the Iran-Contra affair.
   As recently as February, there were upwards of 16,000 rebels
inside Nicaragua attacking Sandinista patrols and sabotaging power
and transportation lines. But in deference to a halting effort at
reaching a negotiated cease-fire, U.S. military aid was suspended
Feb. 29.
   According to intelligence estimates, fewer than 2,000 opposition
troops remain inside Nicaragua, struggling to conserve dwindling
supplies of ammunition. The rest have been starved out, forced to
march weeks through the jungle to reach camps just inside Honduras
where they huddle under black plastic shelters and receive U.S.
food and medicine handouts. Nearby, more than 20,000 Contra family
members subsist in similar camps.
   Supporters who have toured the area say morale among the rebels,
astonishingly, remains good. But anti-Contra lawmakers say that
with Congress having adjourned for the year and no chance for new
military aid on the horizon, the Contras appear finished as a
fighting force.
   The rebels' primary patron, Reagan, can do little more for them.
One candidate to succeed him, Democrat Michael Dukakis, opposes the
Reagan Contra policy. The other, Vice President George Bush, is
talking little about what he would do for the rebels if he takes
office in January, and Contra supporters doubt he will have the
same fervor as Reagan.
   Retired Maj. Gen. John K. Singlaub, who has supported the rebels
for years, last month wrote Bush to warn of an ``impending
disaster'' for the rebels and chastised him for ignoring the issue
in his presidential campaign.
   ``They're moribund,'' said Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., a leader
of House anti-Contra forces. ``For practical purposes, as a
fighting force they're history.''
   One sign that even the rebels' most devoted backers have given
up is their finger-pointing at Democrats.
   ``They are a people to whom this country owes an obligation,''
said Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
   ``Those who want to come to this country are truly refugees.
They would be politically persecuted if they went back to
Nicaragua. We should be talking about reception centers'' in the
United States. ``Fort Worth, Texas, comes to mind,'' Hyde said in a
sarcastic reference to the home district of House Speaker Jim
Wright, the administration's main foe on the Contra issue.
   ``I believe the consequences are going to be very heavy and the
responsibility ought to be very clear,'' added Jeane Kirkpatrick,
Reagan's former United Nations ambassador and a strong Contra
supporter.
   Hyde and Kirkpatrick predicted the failure to oust the
Sandinista regime would lead to increased Soviet influence in the
region and embroil the United States directly in military action to
save nascent democracies in El Salvador and Guatemala.
   Administration policymakers say they may share some of the blame
for the failure of the Contra policy, but say it will be a major
dilemma facing the next occupant of the White House.
   ``Perhaps a new administration will have a different policy
initiative toward all of Central America,'' said one senior
administration official, speaking only on condition of anonymity.
``Perhaps it will be able to sell a program in a way we could never
do. We have not done a very good job of convincing the American
people.''
   While U.S. policy toward the region remains adrift over the next
few months, the region is likely to take another run at a solution.
The presidents of the five Central American countries _ Nicaragua,
Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras _ are talking about
the possibility of a summit meeting in San Salvador just before the
Nov. 14 start of an Organization of American States General
Assembly.
   Complicating their efforts is the continued presence of
thousands of armed rebels along Honduras' border with Nicaragua, a
presence that makes Honduran President Jose Azcona increasingly
nervous. Azcona has suggested a United Nations force be stationed
in the region to keep the borders clear of rebels. Something has to
be done with the Contras, but nobody seems to know exactly what.
   The Contras themselves remain splintered over what to do next.
With U.S. refusal to provide new military aid, some hard-liners
believe the rebels should look to other countries to provide it.
One moderate member of the rebel political directorate, Alfredo
Cesar, wants to return to Nicaragua and work for reform through
peaceful political and diplomatic means.
   ``I don't blame them in the least,'' Edwards said. ``It's
natural that there would be disagreements. They've had their
friends killed, without having achieved anything. (The Sandinistas)
still put people in jail, break up peaceful demonstrations, close
down the press whenever they feel like it. They're still getting
military aid from the Russians. Nothing has changed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
