<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Views Autumn Moon, Reported In Good Spirits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aides held a mirror above Emperor Hirohito's head
Sunday so he could view the full moon, a millennium-old harvest
tradition, palace officials said. They said the ailing emperor was
in good spirits.
   The 87-year-old emperor has joined members of the imperial
family every year to celebrate the Oct. 23 event.
   In London, news reports said British rock guitarist Eric Clapton
has taken out a $105,000 insurance policy in case his concert tour
of Japan, planned for early November, is canceled in deference to
the emperor. The Sun newspaper said Clapton will receive more than
$1.75 million from the policy if the tour is canceled.
   Many other concerts, festivals and other events have been
canceled in Japan because of Hirohito's illness.
   On Sunday, the moon was not visible directly from his bed, so
Hirohito viewed its reflection in a mirror, palace spokesman Kenji
Maeda said.
   Earlier Sunday, Hirohito's blood pressure rose to its highest
level since Sept. 19, when he fell ill.
   Maeda said Hirohito's blood pressure was 174 over 76 in the
afternoon but declined at night to 160 over 78. A normal reading is
about 120 over 80.
   The emperor was in good spirits and chatted with aides and
family members, Maeda said.
   He said Hirohito's anemia had improved slightly following recent
blood transfusions. The emperor has received nearly 25 pints of
blood since Sept. 19.
   The emperor received no transfusions on Sunday, Maeda said.
   Palace officials have refused to confirm or deny news reports
the emperor has cancer in his upper digestive system.
   Hirohito has eaten only a few spoonfuls of porridge in the past
month and has been fed intravenously.
</TEXT>
