<DOCNO> AP881023-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CampaignAds Bjt   10-23 0898</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Ads, Bjt,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Message: Bush Ad People Outflank Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush is running an
advertising campaign so successful that it has overshadowed news
events and swayed voters in a near-vacuum that Democrat Michael
Dukakis only now is moving to fill.
   With the Nov. 8 election little more than two weeks away,
Dukakis went on the air during the weekend with strong
counterpunches to a months-old Bush offensive that raked him over
the coals _ often inaccurately _ and obliterated any momentum the
Massachusetts governor had leaving the Democratic convention in
July.
   From the first commercials filled with children and warmth,
balloons and adulation, to stinging ads attacking Dukakis to a
series of foreign affairs spots stressing the vice president's
experience, Bush's ad people sought to transform his image from
wimp to strong yet sensitive leader.
   They have not made a false move.
   At the same time, Bush's ads have battered Dukakis to the point
that voters who once viewed him as a competent, innovative governor
or _ at worst _ an unknown, tend to see the Democratic nominee as
soft on crime, weak on defense and questionable on the environment.
   Dukakis' own advertising got off to a late and shaky start,
which was an unexpected bonus for Bush and his highly experienced
media team led by Roger Ailes.
   ``If Roger Ailes was working for Dukakis, he would be the
front-runner,'' said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, a University of Texas
professor specializing in political communication.
   Jamieson and other experts say that, in contrast to Bush, the
Dukakis media campaign has been damagingly out of sync. Television
viewers saw nothing that countered Bush's attacks on crime and the
environment.
   Instead, they say, there were celebratory Atlanta convention
scenes a month later, and obscure ``packaging of George Bush''
commercials when voters needed to know more about Dukakis and his
record.
   In lengthy television appearances between now and Election Day,
Dukakis hopes to publicize his record and persuade voters to take
one more look at him _ and Bush _ before they make up their minds.
   On Friday, Dukakis came out slugging. He began airing a series
of blistering TV ads during the weekend in which he appears in
shirtsleeves to accuse Bush of broadcasting claims that are ``full
of lies'' and ``dragging the truth into the gutter'' about the
Democratic nominee's positions on crime and defense.
   He personally goes on the attack against Bush and his running
mate, Dan Quayle, mentioning both by name. One TV ad savages the
vice president's anti-drug leadership, showing scenes of children
buying drugs and Bush meeting with Panamanian leader Manuel Noriega.
   ``Dukakis has re-entered the campaign dialogue doing the job
that a candidate is supposed to do _ engage the claims of the other
candidate and when they are distorted, point that out,'' said
Jamieson.
   ``It's a good move in the ninth hour. It would have been a
better move in the first hour,'' she said, expressing a view shared
by Dukakis running mate Lloyd Bentsen.
   ``If he'd done this as soon as the attacks went on the air, he'd
be ahead in the polls right now,'' Jamieson said.
   For his part, Bush has used TV ads to reinforce the ``I share
your values, he doesn't'' campaign message he has delivered in
stump speeches across the country.
   The results have been dramatic. Bush started with high negative
ratings and Dukakis with high positive ratings among voters. Recent
polls show those ratings are reversed.
   Pollster Lou Harris said last week that 60 percent of nearly
2,000 likely voters surveyed by his organization remembered a Bush
ad attacking the Massachusetts prison furlough program. Most found
it ``too negative and unfair,'' but they also said it was effective.
   ``The Bush commercials have had an enormous impact,'' Harris
said. ``Really more than the debates, more than anything else, they
have determined the set of the election up until now.''
   Julian Cantor, a political advertising expert at the University
of Oklahoma, said Dukakis has reduced crime and strengthened the
police in Massachusetts and received a national award from a crime
victims' assistance group, yet he seems to be a willing victim
himself.
   ``He's been an effective governor in terms of crime. The public
is being left with a very distorted perception,'' Cantor said.
``It's Bush's fault for creating the distortion, but it's Dukakis'
fault for not setting the record straight.''
   Dukakis' endorsement by the League of Conservation Voters was
overshadowed by Bush's personal appearance in Boston Harbor and
follow-up ads accusing the governor of failing to rid the harbor of
pollution, Cantor says.
   ``The Dukakis campaign failed to get out front on the (harbor)
issue or respond to the charge rapidly after it was made,'' he
said. ``If you don't respond, the public accepts the charge as
valid.''
   Dukakis' weak media performance has been attributed to friction
and confusion among his advertising people, and a misguided belief
that he could sit on a 17-point lead in the polls and wait for Bush
to self-destruct.
   Those days appear to have vanished with Dukakis' belated
realization that he must join the fray and cut through what one of
his aides, Leslie Dach, termed a Bush campaign of ``labels, fog and
deceptions.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Jill Lawrence covers media and the presidential
election for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
