<DOCNO> AP881023-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SexQuestions     10-23 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sex Questions,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Survey Asks Welfare Mother Sex Questions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state paternity survey that asks for
intimate details of a welfare mother's sex life is so intrusive
it's offensive, a legal aid lawyer says.
   One federal official said such surveys are discouraged.
   Human Services Department officials confirm that the survey asks
women for the exact dates when sexual relations between them and
the childrens' alleged fathers began and ended, according to the
Charleston Sunday Gazette-Mail.
   Other questions include: ``Is there anyone else who could
possibly be the father of the child? Did the child's father ever
suggest an abortion? How often did you have sexual relations with
him?''
   ``Why don't I just put a video camera in my bedroom,'' one
unidentified woman complained to the newspaper.
   Human Services Commissioner Reginia Lipscomb said the survey is
used to identify the child's father and is federally approved.
   A department employee said the questionnaire does not ask even
more personal questions that might turn up later if the matter went
to court _ such as details of the mother's menstrual cycle, her use
of contraceptives, and the names of other sexual partners.
   Lipscomb said the form was mailed to women in Kanawha County,
which includes Charleston, who collect or have collected Aid to
Families with Dependent Children and whose last names begin with
letters K to Z. She said she did not know how many of the forms
were sent.
   ``My problem with the questionnaire is that it did not seem to
be reasonably limited to the cases where information would be
needed,'' said Bruce Perrone of the Legal Aid Society of Charleston.
   ``It was being sent out in a blanket format to all sorts of
women. I find that grossly intrusive and offensive. There should be
some screening procedure for who this is sent to.''
   Lipscomb said she has no problem with the survey and thinks the
only mistake the department made was to send it through the mail.
She declined to comment about specific questions.
   Lipscomb said federal law requires the state to learn the
identity of fathers of nearly all children being raised by mothers
who collect public assistance. The state then tries to collect
child support from those fathers.
   She said the survey was adapted from other federal forms and
received federal approval.
   A federal official disagreed.
   George Hurley of the Mid-Atlantic Region III of the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services said his office does not
get involved with individual state questionnaires and even
discourages the use of paternity questionnaires.
   ``We are concerned about their use and wonder if they are really
necessary,'' Hurley said.
   In 1982, a federal judge ordered the California Department of
Human Services to interview clients in person when trying to
establish paternity. The judge also told the department to develop
separate sets of questions, so that extremely personal questions
were not asked in cases where paternity was not in question.
   Paternal support is a problem in West Virginia. A Congressional
report says fewer men in West Virginia pay support for their
children than in almost all other states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-MinnesotaSenate Bjt   10-23 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minnesota Senate, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Humphrey Legacy Hasn't Given Son Free Ride To Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The memory of Hubert H. Humphrey has not
given his son, the Democratic Senate nominee, a free ride to
Washington.
   Hubert H. ``Skip'' Humphrey III has trailed Sen. Dave
Durenberger, R-Minn., throughout the fall campaign, though
Democratic Party strategists say Humphrey might score an upset on
Nov. 8.
   Humphrey also has lagged by at least a 2-1 margin in fund
raising for a contest that could cost more than $10 million.
   ``There's no question the spirit of Hubert Humphrey has played
an enormous role'' in the Minnesota race, said Republican
consultant Bob Anderson. ``His (Skip's) name recognition and his
support, his entry into the ... party has come because of his
relationship to his father.''
   Jesse Jackson, in a campaign appearance last week, recalled that
Humphrey's father led the fight for civil rights at the 1948
Democratic National Convention.
   ``The acorn does not fall far from the tree,'' Jackson said.
   Skip Humphrey anticipated Republican claims that he would trade
on the reputation of his father, who served in the Senate from 1949
to 1964 and again from 1971 until his death in January 1978. The
elder Humphrey also served as Lyndon Johnson's vice president and
was the unsuccessful Democratic presidential nominee in 1968.
   ``I bear a famous name, made famous not by me but by my father
and my mother,'' said Humphrey, 46, when he entered the Senate race
in February.
   Humphrey's mother, Muriel Humphrey Brown, was appointed to
succeed his father and served in the Senate until November 1978,
when Durenberger, 54, was elected to succeed her.
   Humphrey says he is running on his own record as Minnesota
attorney general since 1983 and as a former state senator.
   ``I will not trade on what I have not earned,'' Humphrey said.
``I will build on what I have been given.''
   Republicans contend that his magic name is Humphrey's biggest
asset. After 10 years in the state Senate, Humphrey won his first
statewide race for attorney general in 1982 with 1.08 million
votes, the top vote-getter in that election.
   But if his name has helped, being the son of the famous ``Happy
Warrior'' of a generation of Democratic politics also has been a
burden.
   ``As he would be the first to admit, his father was one of a
kind, and you can't help but come up wanting in a comparison such
as that,'' said D.J. Leary, a political analyst and former adviser
to the elder Humphrey.
   One Republican wag has suggested that if Humphrey presented an
opening, Durenberger could retort: ``I knew your father, and you're
no Hubert Humphrey.''
   If Humphrey has been reluctant to invoke his father's name,
Durenberger has been almost eager to do so.
   After Humphrey aired his first ad attacking Durenberger last
spring, the incumbent retorted in a commercial that the attack was
unbefitting the Humphrey name.
   ``Skip's mudslinging doesn't fit in Minnesota,'' Durenberger
said. ``Skip's great, late father never would have started a
campaign this way. Skip's father knew Minnesota.''
   But it was a different Minnesota that Humphrey's father knew,
when the state had a reputation for liberalism. In a Minnesota Poll
released last week by the Star Tribune of Minneapolis, only 29
percent of the respondents said they were liberal, while 53 percent
described themselves as conservatives and 14 percent said they were
moderates.
   Durenberger survived a troubled period in his personal life. He
has reconciled with his wife after they were separated from
February 1985 to October 1986. During the separation, Durenberger,
who is Roman Catholic, moved into a Christian retreat house for
several months.
   He also was arrested and charged with disorderly conduct after a
shouting match with a police officer at Boston's Logan Airport in a
dispute over a taxi.
   Each candidate has retained a high-priced East Coast consultant
to help draw comparisons between them in an increasingly negative
TV ad war.
   Humphrey's ads have accused Durenberger of voting to increase
defense spending and cut Medicare, spurning funds for anti-drug
programs while voting to send foreign aid to countries ``that
actually sell illegal drugs here,'' and helping write legislation
that forced rural hospitals to close.
   Durenberger has responded in kind. A recent Durenberger ad says
that although Humphrey's most important job as attorney general was
to fight crime, ``violent crime in Minnesota has mushroomed'' since
he took office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
