<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LastTemptation-Fire     10-23 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Last Temptation-Fire,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moviegoers Searched After Fire At Showing Of `Temptation'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security was tightened Sunday at a theater showing
``The Last Temptation of Christ'' after a fire closed another
cinema running the controversial film and injured 10 people.
   The fire Saturday night at the St. Michel cinema on the Left
Bank began as patrons were leaving and apparently started in a
theater seat. The blaze heavily damaged the building, the site of
religious protests against the film.
   On Sunday, security guards were posted outside the Gaumont
Champs-Elysees theater, the only other Paris house showing the film.
   The blaze was under investigation by the criminal brigade of the
city police department, the unit that investigates cases of
suspected arson.
   Paris Archbishop Jean-Marie Lustiger condemned the fire and told
those who have been demonstrating against the film, ``You believe
you are defending Christ, but you are doing exactly the contrary.''
   ``You are not behaving as Christians but as enemies of Christ,''
said Lustiger, speaking during a break at a conference in Lourdes.
   The Communist Party in Paris called for a demonstration Monday
outside the St. Michel cinema to protest attempts to inhibit
artistic freedom.
   Jean Desandre, a spokesman for the Gaumont Champs-Elysees, said
management had instructed employees to be ``vigilant from the day
the film opened.'' He said the increased security was ``necessary''
and that people buying tickets to the film were being searched in
the theater lobby.
   A sign posted at the front of the theater said, ``Because of
provocative incidents by unscrupulous spectators, the public is
advised that a search will be conducted before the entrance to the
cinema.''
   The film, an adaptation of the 1955 Nikos Kazanthakis novel, led
to protests by Christian groups elsewhere in Europe and in the
United States.
   Some Christians have been offended by the film's portrayal of
Jesus Christ as a human being with passions and weaknesses. The
film includes a short scene in which Christ imagines having sex
with Mary Magdalene.
</TEXT>
