<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     10-23 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELY, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Moose Lodge seemed too obvious a stop, so
the meandering mammal headed for the high school in search of peace
and quiet.
   But authorities decided the school wasn't an appropriate stop
either for the visiting moose cow, which was trying to make its way
through town and away from all those excited people with cameras.
   ``We were afraid, because at the school there are all kinds of
windows; if she had taken a jump, she would probably have had to
have been destroyed,'' said police officer John Saw in this town of
4,800.
   So police and state wildlife officers blocked off traffic and,
following the loose moose on foot, gradually herded it back to the
vicinity of the Moose Lodge in this town in the forests and lakes
of northeastern Minnesota.
   That sounds easier than it was. Sometimes curious people got in
the moose's path and it veered away.
   ``Heck, nobody's seen a moose for years and years in the city of
Ely,'' Saw said.
   Eventually the moose made it safely across a highway and a golf
course, past the Moose Lodge, away from all those annoying people
and into the deep woods, said Al Heidebrink of the state Department
of Natural Resources.
   Heidebrink used to work in Grand Marais, over on Lake Superior.
Moose aren't as uncommon there, he said, and people usually just
ignore them while they find the road out of town on their own.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOONE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They've competed as a centipede, and as Snow
White and the Seven Dwarfs, and this year they were 14 Elvis
Presley impersonators, braving wind and sleet to run in the fifth
annual Other Big Apple Road Race.
   When the Appalachian State University race began four years ago,
several of the English department faculty and their families
decided to run as a group. In addition to the centipede and Snow
White and her crowd, they've competed as the Mickey Mouse Club and
a chain gang.
   Saturday's effort featured homemade Elvis masks, T-shirts
decorated with Elvis song titles, and a portable stereo playing the
King's music along the race route.
   The first Elvis over the line was Karen Carmine, an English
professor at Converse College whose husband is on the ASU English
faculty. She covered the four miles in 38 minutes to finigh 290th
out of 525 runners.
   ``That's a pretty good time for a dead person,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GERING, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Here's our lard, Lord!'' cried the Rev.
Neal Hail as two congregations weighed in to start a contest of
calories.
   Hail of the ``First Fatties'' First Assembly of God Church of
Scottsbluff challenged the Rev. William Bibb of the ``Northfield
Porkers'' from Northfield Church at Gering to a month-long diet
derby.
   The two teams, with about 50 members each, weighed in Saturday.
   The Northfield team weighed 3,800 pounds and the First Assembly
team tipped the scapes at 5,140 pounds.
   The dieters will weigh again on Nov. 19 to see which team has
shed the most pounts, Bibb said.
   But their goals may be suspect.
   The losing team will play host to a ``pig-out'' party for the
winners, Bibb said.
