<HEAD>Police Say Man Headed Toward Minister With Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Sunday they
arrested a man with a mine within 500 feet from the minister of law
and order, who was opening a new police station in the black
township of Crossroads.
   Police said the arrest was made at 11:16 a.m. Saturday, shortly
after Adriaan Vlok arrived to open the police station in the
squatter camp outside Cape Town.
   The government tried several times to destroy Crossroads before
recently making it a legal township.
   Statements issued by the police and the Ministry of Law and
Order did not identify the man, who was arrested on a charge of
terrorism.
   Police said he was being treated at a hospital because he had
complained of dizziness after his arrest. Police said the event was
not reported on the day it happened because the investigation was
still continuing.
   The Ministry of Law and Order said two policemen arrested the
suspect ``about 150 meters from where the minister was officiating.
... The alleged terrorist, who was moving in the direction of the
new police station, was in possession of an SPM limpet mine'' and a
detonator.
   The statement said that a search of the suspect's living
quarters revealed documents of the African National Congress, the
outlawed guerrilla organization waging a sabotage and bombing
campaign to end the apartheid system of racial segregation and
white privilege.
   The ministry statement said two policemen in a patrol vehicle
spotted the man acting suspiciously, turned their car around and
chased the suspect. It said the man was carrying the mine and
detonator in a bag.
