<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1403EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Beatification     10-23 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Beatification,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Beatifies 17th Century Danish Scientist, Bishop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Sunday beatified a 17th
century Danish scientist who converted to Catholicism and served as
a bishop in predominantly Protestant Germany.
   During the solemn ceremony in St. Peter's Basilica, the pope
praised Niels Stensen as an example for scientists, missionaries
and Christians around the world.
   ``All his life, Niels Stensen tirelessly sought the truth,
scientific and religious, in the conviction that every discovery,
no matter how modest, marks a step ahead toward absolute truth,''
the pope said.
   ``A top scientist never satisfied with just hypothesis and
always in search of complete certainty, he was especially moved to
discover the ultimate reason for everything: God, who can't be
discovered with the most sophisticated instruments of science ...
but only through the science of the heart,'' the pope said.
   Stensen was born a Lutheran in Copenhagen in 1638. After
studying medicine in Holland, he moved to Florence, Italy and
converted to Catholicism in 1667.
   He was appointed bishop in Germany, where he died in Schwerin in
1686. He was buried in Florence's Basilica of St. Lorenzo.
   ``His mission in a predominantly Protestant country shows how
honesty, combined with distinction and discretion, can and should
establish those relations which facilitate mutual understanding,
love and unity,'' John Paul said.
   The pope said Stensen should serve as inspiration for Christians
living outside their native lands, ``in solitude or in places that
don't understand them.''
   The ceremony was concelebrated by 10 cardinals and bishops from
Italy, West Germany and Denmark. About 1,000 Danish pilgrims
attended.
   Beatification is a step toward possible sainthood in the Roman
Catholic Church.
</TEXT>
