<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Joan-Britain 1stLd-Writethru   10-23 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Joan-Britain, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0712,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Of Devastated Nicaraguan City Appeals For Aid</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs to add that Nicaraguan minister of state
also on trip, ADDS quotes. Pick up 6th pvs, `The mayor...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Joan-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of the Nicaraguan city of Bluefields,
which was devastated by Hurricane Joan, appealed for urgent aid
Sunday to help his city and the storm victims.
   ``We are sending out an SOS to governments, agencies, to the
people in general for urgently needed help ... in whatever area,
health, food, clothing, construction materials and practically
everything,'' said Mayor Henningston Omeir.
   Omeir and Lumberto Campbell, Nicaragua's minister of state, are
part of a delegation that has been visiting Denmark, Norway,
Belgium and Britain to seek support for development projects. Both
men said the delegation had now decided to focus on aid for the
hurricane victims.
   Hurricane Joan tore across Nicaragua on Saturday with winds of
125 mph and torrential rains. Dozens of people were killed in the
storm.
   Nicaraguan radio reported the hurricane destroyed 90 percent of
the homes in Bluefields, a coastal city of 60,000 about 180 miles
east of the capital, Managua.
   Campbell and Omeir said the hurricane had destroyed the economy
of a region which has little infrastructure and was already
suffering serious economic problems.
   In Bluefields, where the main source of income is fishing,
Campbell said two fishing plants were blown down.
   The mayor said his wife, son and parents are in Bluefields and
that he last spoke to them on Wednesday because the hurricane cut
communications to the area.
   ``At first, since I have my family and friends and everyone at
home, I would like to be home,'' he said. ``But I realize going
home without some help means nothing.''
   Omeir said most of the 5,500 homes in Bluefields are modest
wooden homes built on stilts.
   ``Near the water side (the houses) were right in front of the
bay. So I can't imagine them still standing, those at least at the
front of the bay,'' he said.
   The largest building in Bluefields is the hospital. ``Let's hope
it's still standing,'' Omeir said.
   The delegation had planned to return to Nicaragua in the middle
of the week, but Omeir said the visit may be extended to continue
the appeal for aid.
   The Foreign Office said Britain, through its ambassador to
Nicargua, had donated $17,500 in cash to a relief organization in
Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
