<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeirutBombingRemembrance     10-23 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beirut Bombing Remembrance,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Servicemen Killed in 1983 Beirut Bombing Honored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 people, many of them relatives
of victims, honored the 241 American servicemen and 56 French
paratroopers killed in terrorist attacks five years ago in Beirut.
   In a brief wreath-laying ceremony at Arlington National Cemetery
where some of the American victims are buried, Marine Corps Maj.
Gen. Robert Winglass said they will be remembered as turning world
opinion against terrorists.
   ``That's the great lesson that's learned from the Beirut
experience,'' Winglass told the solemn gathering. ``That terrorism
is wrong; it is no longer recognized by any person of any stature
and dignity as having any foundation in principle.''
   The Oct. 23, 1983, attack on a Marine compound at the Beirut
airport by a truck laden with 12,000 pounds of explosives
eventually prompted the Reagan administration to withdraw 1,800
U.S. military troops in Lebanon as part of an international
peacekeeping force.
   ``It is difficult to recall the horror, the devastation and the
agonies that preceded this day five years ago,'' said John Knipple
of Alexandria, whose son, Lance Cpl. James Knipple, was killed in
the attack. ``They need to be honored, they need to be remembered.''
   Kevin Jiggets, then a lance corporal in Beirut and a survivor of
the explosion, said the ceremony also was to ``pay tribute to all
the victims of terrorist acts and their families.''
   The French paratroopers were killed the same day as the
Americans in a separate terrorist attack in another part of Beirut.
   The service was sponsored by No Greater Love, a 17-year-old
humanitarian organization devoted to helping families who have lost
loved ones in wars or by acts of terrorism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
