<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   10-23 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0714,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran To Allow Political Parties</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 7th graf, `The main...' to clarify that main party no
longer operating. PIck up 8th graf, `A Parties...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's information minister said
political parties, sharply limited for years, will be allowed to
operate freely if they do not conspire against the Islamic
government.
   An opposition group called the announcement ``nothing new.''
   Minister Mohammad Mohammadi Reyshahri, in a statement broadcast
Sunday, said as long as the parties ``demonstrate their commitment
to the Islamic system and abide by their commitments in action,
they can operate freely.''
   The statement, made Saturday and carried by the official Islamic
Republic News Agency, said there would be limits on party
activities but did not spell them out. The IRNA report was
monitored in Nicosia.
   Rifts between different groups led to armed clashes between the
opposition groups and government forces in June 1981, two years
after the Islamic revolution that toppled the shah, Mohammed Reza
Pahlavi. Most parties were banned, including the Mujehedeen Khalq
Organization and the monarchists.
   The pro-Moscow Tudeh party was banned in early 1984. Several
groups went underground and worked clandestinely after the ban.
   The main government party, the Islamic Republic Party, and other
Islamic groups continued to operate legally. But Iran's
revolutionary leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, abolished the
IRP in June 1987, after President Ali Khamenei and Parliament
Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani said there was no need for it.
   A Parties Act passed by the Majlis, or Parliament, in August
1981, provided for political groups to operate legally as long as
they upheld the constitution. Groups were outlawed if they
undermined national unity, sowed discord, violated the principals
of Islam or the Islamic foundations of the country, or received
foreign aid.
   Parliament had not passed the act's enforcement procedures and
with the minister's statement, the government appeared to lay the
groundwork for that.
   In Baghdad, Iraq, a spokesman for the Mujahedeen Khalq scoffed
at the Iranian information minister's announcement.
   Spokesman Ali Reza Jaferzada said it was ``nothing new and was
made for external consumption.''
   ``The regime is besieged by international condemnation for its
massive executions and this is an attempt to beautify its ugly
image,'' the spokesman said.
   The opposition group charges that tens of thousands of political
opponents have been jailed and executed.
   The group had joined Iraq in fighting Iran during the 8-year
Iran-Iraq war. Iran and Iraq ceased fire Aug. 20 under a
U.N.-mediated peace agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VincennesHomecoming 1stLd-Writethru a0726 10-23 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes Homecoming, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0726,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ship That Mistakenly Shot Down Iranian Airliner Returning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Speakers at ...' to CORRECT that ship was not
named for city.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Monday is homecoming day for the USS Vincennes,
the ship that mistakenly shot down an Iranian airliner, and the
Navy is trying to remove any unease by bringing out a band and the
crew's wives and girlfriends.
   ``This is not one of those Vietnam things with the ship coming
in at midnight,'' Navy spokesman Cmdr. David Dillon said. ``We're
not going to sneak the ship in. We're inviting people to watch.
People understand this was an arduous deployment. The sailors have
a lot of public support.''
   The welcoming for the cruiser won't be any different than the
ones given to any other Navy ship returning from an extended
deployment, officials said.
   A Navy band will play the ``normal John Phillip Sousa-type
stuff,'' said Senior Chief Petty Officer Steve Hiney. ``It's going
to be a big story and we understand that (but) it's a regular, old
homecoming we're planning.
   ``Excited family members will be on the pier and excited sailors
on the ship. There's going to be punch and cookies. New fathers are
going to be seeing new kids for the first time. The wives and
girlfriends, mothers and fathers are going to be there.''
   Speakers at the welcoming include William Rose, mayor of
Vincennes, Ind., the city which like the ship was named for a
Revolutionary War battle, and Rep. Bill Lowery, R-Calif.
   Lowery organized a volunteer effort that gathered 10,000
signatures and sent the messages of support to the crew in the
Persian Gulf after the July 3 accidental downing of the Iranian
airliner. All 290 people aboard the civilian jet were killed.
   ``I empathized with how low the crew, the officers and the
skipper (Capt. Will Rogers III) were feeling,'' Lowery said.
``Their sense of isolation and anguish, because of the civilian
casualties on that airplane, they had to be feeling incredibly low.
   ``I just wanted to let them know that we understood. They were
defending their country to the best of their ability and that we
were not passing judgment ... They needed to know they were not
being abandoned.''
   The official Pentagon report concluded that the Vincennes
mistook the airliner for an Iranian F-14 fighter jet and blamed
misinterpreted readings of computer and radar data on crew stress
in a first-time combat situation. The Vincennes was engaged in a
firefight with several Iranian gunboats at the time.
   Dr. Thomas Rusk, a clinical associate professor of psychiatry,
said ending the Vincennes' tragedy-marred 180-day deployment with a
``normal'' greeting is the best way to smooth the sailors' reunion
with their families as well as society.
   ``I think that's absolutely indicated and I applaud the Navy for
doing that,'' said Rusk, who also works with police officers
involved in shootings in his private practice and formerly
counseled Air Force personnel while in the service.
   ``These people did the best they could. It's terrific that they
are being welcomed home just like anybody else,'' he said.
   But Rusk, a University of California, San Diego, clinical
faculty member, said it may be a difficult homecoming for those who
either were involved in the chain of command that led to the
decision to fire the missile or who are emotionally unable to open
up to others about their anguish.
   ``There's a grieving process here because you don't come back as
heroes,'' Rusk said. There may be the perception ``you come back as
inadvertent screw-ups. You grieve the sense of failure, the sense
of loss.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
