<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1442EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Homeless-Sanitation     10-23 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless-Sanitation,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless Complain of Sanitation Clean-Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City efforts to keep Manhattan sidewalks clear
of debris are drawing complaints from street people who say
sanitation workers are carting off their belongings.
   The clean-up began months ago after residents on the Lower East
Side complained of mattresses, box springs and cardboard boxes
blocking sidewalks near a city-run men's shelter, the Sanitation
Department said.
   Two garbage trucks, four sanitation workers and several police
officers sweep the area once every week or two, said department
spokesman Vito Turso. ``Our job is to keep the streets clean,'' he
said. ``We do it under police supervision, because some of the
(homeless) people are pretty hostile.''
   But an advocate for the homeless saw it differently.
   ``We've had about a dozen complaints of homeless people getting
their belongings taken and thrown into garbage trucks,'' said
Robert Hayes, counsel for the Coalition for the Homeless.
   ``They took my ID, clothes, shorts, sleeping bag, everything I
had,'' said Robert Lee Marion, 47, who sleeps on a sidewalk. ``They
took my American flag, about 500 records, six to eight boxes of
books. It's terrorism.''
   Police said people who are blocking the sidewalk are asked to
move along with their belongings. If items are abandoned on the
street, they are considered garbage and thrown away.
   ``Everybody has a right to be on the street,'' said Sgt. John
Clifford, a spokesman for the Police Department. ``People do not
have the right to be on the street and litter.''
</TEXT>
