<DOCNO> AP881023-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     10-23 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Just Say No,' A Farce By Larry Kramer, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Kramer's ``Just Say No'' is a sledgehammer
farce, battering everybody in sight, including the audience.
   It's nasty, savage, mean-spirited, unnerving, often in bad taste
and surprisingly, considering the possibilities, only sporadically
funny. That may be the fault of director David Esbjornson, who has
supervised the frantic door-slamming and bed-hopping with a heavy
hand and has neglected the comedy.
   The play, which arrived Thursday at off-Broadway's WPA Theater,
requires a not very great leap of imagination to identify its
supposedly fictional characters. The program proclaims ``any
resemblance to actual events, or to persons living or dead, is in
the eye of the beholder.'' Don't believe it.
   The chararcters include the closeted homosexual mayor of the
northeast's largest city; the termagant, clothes-horse wife of the
country's potentate who is called ``Daddy'' by just about everybody
in the play and the couple's ballet dancer son who lusts after his
Secret Service escorts.
   The play is set in the plush townhouse of Foppy Schwartz, the
gay confidant and lunch buddy to Mrs. Potentate. It's Foppy,
self-derided as ``the flower behind the drone,'' who sets the farce
spinning. He's galvanized into action as a crusader for gay rights
when he acquires a videotape of sexual hijinks by people in high
places.
   Blackmail is the order of the day as the tape is passed around
as frequently as the bodies. Of course, the bad guys win out in
this morality tale. And Kramer supplies a chilling finale that is
the best moment in the play. Until then, the playwright scatters
his potshots, shooting wildly at every alleged governmental
conspiracy of the last 25 years.
   But much of it is not very funny. Many of the jokes depend on
name recognition; those names that have not been changed to protect
the guilty.
   The acting doesn't help matters. Only David Margulies as the
epicene Foppy manages to be outrageous and affecting at the same
time. Kathleen Chalfant bears a striking resemblance to a certain
first lady. The others are given to hyperventilating, particularly
Joseph Ragno as the mayor and Keith Reddin as his boyfriend.
   In ``The Normal Heart,'' his best known play, Kramer was not
afraid to shout, telling the world about the inaction and
indifference in the government's fight againt AIDS.
   He shouts in ``Just Say No,'' but the sound is shriller, less
personal and more diffuse. This time, you can't hear the play for
all the yelling going on.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Election-Blacks 1stLd-Writethru a0724 10-23 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Election-Blacks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blacks Hope to Add House Seat in November</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs grafs 19,20,22, bgng, But she, to CORRECT
identification of Walters and Williams.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks hope to pick up at least one new House
member in the Nov. 8 elections but aren't optimistic that their
biggest political boost of the year _ Jesse Jackson's strong
showing in the Democratic primaries _ will result in major
congressional gains.
   If all 23 black House members win re-election and Donald Payne,
a Newark, N.J., councilman takes a vacant seat as expected, the
number of blacks in Congress will be at its highest level ever.
   All the House incumbents are Democrats and only one, Rep.
Cardiss Collins of Illinois, is a female.
   Payne, a Democrat running against black Republican Michael Webb,
is the front-runner in the race for the seat left open by the
retirement of Rep. Peter Rodino, D-N.J., chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee who has represented his predominantly black
district since 1948.
   The Congressional Black Caucus is cautiously optimistic about
picking up a seat in Louisiana's 8th district where attorney Faye
Williams is fighting a rematch against Rep. Clyde Holloway, the
one-term Republican.
   ``Faye is in a dead heat right now.'' said Rep. Mervyn M.
Dymally, D-Calif., caucus chairman. ``She does have a chance.''
   Another black challenger, Democrat Betty Wimbush, has virtually
no chance of upsetting Rep. Bill Young, a popular Republican who
has represented the St. Petersburg, Fla., area since 1970.
   Black Rep. Mike Espy, D-Miss., elected in 1986, must fend off an
enthusiastic challenge from Republican businessman Jack Coleman in
the 2nd district where blacks slightly outnumber whites.
   Ron Walters, a political science professor at Howard University,
said Espy ``might have a coattail problem'' if white voters turn
out heavily for GOP nominee George Bush and Rep. Trent Lott,
R-Miss., who is running for a vacant Senate seat.
   Blacks are keeping a close eye on Rep. Alan Wheat, D-Mo.
Although he was expected to win election to a fourth term, Wheat is
one of the few blacks elected to Congress from a majority white
district. His opponent in Kansas City is community activist Mary
Ellen Lobb.
   In an unusual development in the Senate, two black Republican
candidates _ Alan Keyes in Maryland and Maurice Dawkins of Virginia
_ are running against two popular Democrats. Neither Republican is
given any chance of winning.
   Keyes, a former State Department official, is challenging Sen.
Paul Sarbanes, while Dawkins, a one-time civil rights activist with
conservative views, is opposing former Gov. Charles Robb,
son-in-law of the late President Johnson.
   Linda Williams, an analyst at the Joint Center for Political
Studies, a research organization that focuses on black political
affairs, said Keyes and Dawkins were chosen to run in ``no-win
races.''
   Nevertheless, she said, the Republican Party will earn ``some
brownie points with black Americans'' by selecting two black
candidates for the Senate.
   The only black elected to the Senate since Reconstruction was
Edward Brooke, a Massachusetts Republican who was defeated in 1978.
   Despite Jackson's second-place finish in the Democratic
presidential primaries behind Michael Dukakis, some blacks hold
little hope of future gains in Congress unless more white Americans
can be persuaded to vote for black candidates.
   Walters doubts this will happen in the near future ``because of
race politics in America.''
   Some black politicians, such as Virginia Lt. Gov. Douglas Wilder
manage to win white support by appealing to middle-income
Americans, Walters said. Wilder stressed his government experience
when he was elected in 1986.
   But Walters said the toughest races for black congressional
candidates are those in districts where a large segment of the
white population is at the lower end of the socio-economic scale.
   It is easier for blacks in the higher-income white districts,
which tend to be more liberal, Walters said. For instance,
Jackson's white support came primarily from ``the neo-liberal wing
of the yuppies,'' Williams said.
   Even so, she said, Jackson only received about 20 percent of the
white vote, about the same as successful black mayoral candidates.
   But Williams said the positive impact of the Jackson campaign is
that ``more blacks will run in places where they would not have run
before.'' She said there are about 7,000 local black officeholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
