<DOCNO> AP881023-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChurchFarmAid     10-23 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church Farm Aid,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Diocese Gives Interest Free Loans To Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRI COLBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholics in central Illinois
offer prayers for farmers in trouble, but they're also sending a
little cash along with the good thoughts this year.
   The Diocese of Springfield, which covers 28 counties, is
offering interest-free loans of up to $2,000 to area farmers,
regardless of religious affiliation.
   ``We would like to (give) some generous help which comes from
the same heart that our prayers come from,'' says Bishop Daniel
Ryan, who heads the diocese.
   Applications will be accepted starting next month for the 1989
loan program, dubbed Project Isidore for the patron saint of
farmers. For the 1988 growing season, the program's first, about 40
loans averaging $1,000 were made. ``The purpose of the project is
to provide funds for farmers who are hurting, funds which would
help them not to turn away foreclosure on their properties, I'm
sorry to say, but which would give them some money for seed or
fertilizer or important things like that,'' Ryan said.
   Diocesan officials say the small loans won't save failing farms
but might make a difference for farmers who need help.
   ``We just don't have the availability of funds to stave off
these enormous problems which face our farmers,'' Ryan said, ``but
we wanted in a realistic way to help them with some items with
which we could be of help.''
   The loans are intended to help farmers with spring planting
needs for fuel, seed, feed, fertilizer and chemicals. Farmers can
apply between Nov. 7 and Feb. 1, and loan checks will be mailed by
the end of February.
   Ryan said the money for the program was not from the collection
plate but from donors who have chosen to remain anonymous.
   The size of this year's program will depend in part on future
donations as well as on the ability of the farmers helped so far to
repay their loans.
   ``We do not demand, but we certainly expect repayment, so that
we can help others who are in similar plights,'' Ryan said.
   The bishop said there could be an increase in the number of
applicants this year because of the drought, which hit Illinois
hard. The U.S. Department of Agriculture estimated earlier this
month that the state's farmers will have the worst corn yield in 28
years and the lowest soybean yield in 14 years.
   Diocese officials say the program, the only one of its kind in
Illinois, is patterned after a similar loan program offered in
Milwaukee.
   Harold Dodd, president of the Illinois Farmers Union, praised
the diocese for getting involved.
   ``I think it's a very commendable thing for the diocese to be
doing this,'' Dodd said. ``I would have to agree that that's not
going to cure people's problems, but every little bit helps.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     10-23 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>4 Guerrillas Die In Clash; Shiite Group Marks 5th Anniversary Of
U.S. Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops and allied militiamen of
the South Lebanon Army clashed Sunday with Palestinian guerrillas
in eastern Lebanon, killing four guerrillas, police said. Israel
radio said six guerrillas died.
   In south Beirut's slums, pro-Iranian Moslem zealots held rallies
to mark the suicide truck bombing of a U.S. Marine base at Beirut
Airport that killed 241 American servicemen Oct. 23, 1983.
   ``This morning, exactly five years ago, the Marines and the
French paratroopers were blown up,'' Hezbollah's spiritual guide,
Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, told the crowd.
   ``Struggle to keep that panic alive. Struggle to keep this power
going everywhere,'' he said.
   A crowd of 3,000 at south Beirut's Bir el-Abed district also
erupted in anti-American and anti-Israeli chants when a Hezbollah
cleric identified the name of the suicide bomber who killed eight
Israeli soldiers in a south Lebanon attack Wednesday.
   In Jerusalem, Israel radio said an Israeli-backed militia may
execute Lebanese suspects by firing squad if a trial determines
they helped pro-Iranians extremists with Wednesday's car bomb. The
Israeli military would not comment on the report.
   About 80 people were detained in connection with the attack, the
Israeli daily Yediot Ahronot and Maariv newspapers reported.
   The sound of machine-gun fire and rocket-propelled grenades
reverberated across the slopes of Mount Hermon, on the northern
edge of Israel's self-designated security zone in south Lebanon.
   A police spokesman in Hasbaya, which overlooks six-by-10-mile
border enclave controlled by Israeli troops and the predominantly
Christian militiamen of the South Lebanon Army, said the battle
lasted five hours.
   Police said four guerrillas were injured.
   The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, led by
Marxist George Habash, later issued a statement in Hasbaya,
claiming its guerrillas attacked the Israeli-Lebanese militia
position and killed or wounded 10. Police said they could not
confirm any Israeli or Lebanese militia casualties.
   The Palestinian group, which has its headquarters in Damascus,
said four guerrillas were missing. The group maintains several
bases behind the Syrian army lines in east Lebanon's Bekaa Valley.
   Hezbollah speakers identified Wednesday's suicide bomber as
Abdallah Atwah, 20, a Shiite whose family lives in Markabah in the
security zone.
   ``Our martyr chose to kill the Israelis with his purified
self,'' said Sheik Naim Kassem. The crowds raised clenched fists
and roared in unison ``War, war unto victory!'' and ``Death to
Israel!''
   The clerics told the Bir el-Abed rally that they delayed the
disclosure of Atwah's identity to coincide with the anniversary of
the Marine base truck bombing.
   The 1983 Beirut attack, the deadliest terrorist strike ever
against the United States, was accompanied by a simultaneous
suicide truck bombing of a French paratroop headquarters in Moslem
west Beirut, which killed 58 Frenchmen.
   The Marines and the French formed the bulk of a multinational
peacekeeping force that tried to end Lebanon's 13-year-old civil
war.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed responsibility for
Wednesday's attack. It said Atwah dedicated the bombing to the
10-month Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied
territories. More than 300 Palestinians and six Israelis have died
in the uprising.
   ``The language of stones with which you are facing Israel is
much stronger than all the weapons on earth,'' said a videotape
purportedly taken of Atwah just before the attack. Hezbollah
released the videotape Sunday.
   Israel avenged the car bombing with air strikes against
Palestinian and Shiite guerrilla bases in south Lebanon Friday,
killing 21 people and wounding 34.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
