<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1627EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietLawyers     10-23 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Lawyers,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Attorneys Hoping To Form Own ABA-Style Organization: Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet attorneys hope reforms in their
country will give them more independence, and are looking to the
American Bar Association as a possible model for a Soviet lawyers
organization, a law journal reports.
   A delegation of lawyers and judges from the Soviet Union met
with their counterparts at ABA offices in Washington and Chicago in
the past two weeks, the legal newspaper, The Daily Journal,
reported in Monday's editions.
   Delegates candidly discussed problems concerning the Soviet
legal system and the effects of Soviet Leader Mikhail Gorbachev's
policy of perestroika, or restructuring, on the legal profession.
   ``We have to have perestroika in the essence of our law,'' said
group leader Venyamin Yakovlev. ``And because advokati (lawyers)
know the practical realities that perestroika can have on the
practice of law, it is important to have an independent union of
lawyers that can push for change.''
   The delegation included a justice of the Latvian Supreme Court,
district judges from Moscow and Leningrad, law professors, several
private attorneys, procurators _ similar to American prosecutors _
and police investigators.
   ``They're interested in our structure as they restructure,''
said ABA president-elect Stanley Chavin. ``They're beginning to
envision the practice of law as a free-standing institution of its
own.''
   Members of the delegation expressed hope that Soviet attorneys
will have a bigger role in shaping their country's laws.
   But Yakovlev said reform may be slow in coming and blamed that
on the bureaucracy at the Ministry of Justice, which he called
``too big, too slow and too slow-thinking.''
   The ministry puts ministry officials on public bodies, evaluates
lawyers' work and regulate the number of lawyers. Some critics say
that people's rights are eroded under the present system, because
for example the state could give a lawyer a poor evaluation for
helping a defendant too strongly.
   ``Psychological preconceptions against change are the main
roadblock we have to remove. The (legal) apparatus still operates
along familiar lines; it's very difficult to cope with new ideas,''
Yakovlev said.
   Some Soviet lawyers envision an attorneys' organization that
would work for an independent judiciary, lobby the Supreme Soviet
on legislation and file ``friend of the court'' briefs before the
Supreme Court in Moscow.
   ``Traditionally, the Soviets never had lobbyists or special
interest groups since they could not acknowledge that people had
interests different than the state,'' said Randy Bregman, program
director at the Institute of International Law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
