<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-PLO,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mubarak: Jordan, PLO Agree To Form Confederation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak said Sunday that
Jordan and the Palestine Liberation Organization have agreed on a
form of a confederation but offered few details on the proposed
union.
   Mubarak made the statement to the state-run Middle East News
Agency upon returning home from meetings with King Hussein of
Jordan, PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat and President Saddam Hussein of
Iraq.
   ``They (Jordan and the PLO) are in agreement on this and
(Arafat) has announced that he is for the confederation with
Jordan,'' Mubarak was quoted as saying.
   He did not elaborate but said King Hussein and Arafat met in an
``extremely cordial atmosphere'' Saturday in Aqaba, Jordan. After
that meeting Mubarak and Arafat flew to Baghdad for the talks with
President Hussein.
   In Aqaba, the Jordanian monarch said Sunday he had agreed with
Arafat ``to continue contacts to coordinate positions in the
service of the Palestinian cause,'' according to Petra, Jordan's
official news agency.
   The agency also said the king ``affirmed the centrality'' of the
PLO's role in the peace process, especially following Jordan's July
31 decision to cut legal links with the Israeli-occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
   The king's remarks were some of the warmest he has made about
the PLO since breaking with the organization in 1986. At that time
he accused the PLO of reneging on agreements dealing with Middle
East peace proposals.
   But on Sunday, Petra said the king ``expressed satisfaction with
the determination of the PLO to shoulder direct responsibility to
attain the aspirations of the Palestinian people and obtain their
legitimate national rights on their own soil.''
   In Baghdad the Egyptian agency quoted Arafat as saying the
weekend talks were ``positive and cordial. We have placed a basis
for a new relation between the PLO and the Jordanian kingdom.''
   Palestinian sources in Baghdad said the weekend negotiations
were aimed at consolidating an Arab position before Israel's Nov. 1
parliamentary election and U.S. presidential balloting Nov. 8.
   The PLO's palriament, the Palestine National Council, is
scheduled to meet next month in Algiers, Algeria. It is expected to
discuss declaring an independent Palestinian state in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, seized from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle
East War.
   More than 300 Palestinians and six Israelis have been slain in a
10-month Palestinian uprising over Israeli rule in the occupied
lands.
   Arab diplomatic sources in Baghdad said Arafat, President
Hussein and Mubarak also agreed on an Arab summit meeting, proposed
by King Hussein, on the Iran-Iraq peace talks and the governmental
crisis in Lebanon.
   Egypt and Jordan supported Iraq in the 8-year-old war with
Irran. Iran and Iraq have maintained a U.N.-mediated Aug. 20
cease-fire.
   Lebanon's Parliament failed to pick a new president last month,
and Christians and Moslems established rival leaderships.
</TEXT>
