<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-23 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow In Upper Midwest, Showers And Thunderstorms In Lower
Mississippi Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell Sunday over the upper Mississippi Valley and in the
western Great Lakes region, and heavy rain fell in parts of the
south-central states.
   While some areas had winter-like weather, Austin, Texas, posted
a record high of 91 and Miami tied its record of 85 degrees.
   A cold front that extended over the upper Great Lakes and middle
Mississippi Valley pushed eastward into the Ohio Valley and sagged
south across the lower Mississippi Valley. Showers and
thunderstorms lined up just ahead of the cold front from
Mississippi into southeastern Texas.
   Thunderstorms produced generous rainfall in parts of Arkansas,
especially in the northwestern corner, where Berryville got 1.34
inches and 1.02 inches fell at Dardendale.
   The cold front extended from a low pressure system over Lake
Michigan, and colder air pulling around the western side of the low
produced light snow during the morning over central and eastern
Minnesota.
   The snow moved into northern Wisconsin and western Upper
Michigan. Iron River, Mich., reported 3 inches of snow with an inch
reported at Calumet. In Wisconsin, up to 2 inches of snow fell
across Oneida County, including Rhinelander, and in parts of Vilas
and Lincoln counties.
   Strong, gusty wind whistled across the middle Mississippi and
lower Missouri valleys during the afternoon, with gusts peaking
between 35 and 50 mph across the eastern sections of South Dakota
and eastern Nebraska into much of Iowa.
   Elsewhere, low pressure drifting northward out of Maine produced
light rain over northern New England.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 91 at McAllen and Harlingen, Texas.
Sunday morning's low was 12 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Monday, widespread showers were forecast throughout the
central and eastern Great Lakes, the upper Ohio Valley and mid
Atlantic region into southern and central New England. Scattered
snow showers were forecast in colder air across the western parts
of the Great Lakes. Scattered showers and thunderstorms were
forecast across northern and central Florida.
   Highs in the 30s were predicted from northern Minnesota into
northern Wisconsin; in the 40s or 50s across much of the nation
east of the Mississippi River; in the 50s over the Northwest, near
the Canadian border, and into the northern Plains; in the 60s or
70s across much of the nation west of the Mississippi, and from the
lower Mississippi Valley into the southern Atlantic region; in the
80s across southern Florida, and from the Rio Grande Valley of
Texas into the valleys of California; and in the 90s across the
desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
