<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Violence,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LA Gang Members Crash Sweet 16 Party, Kill One Wound Two</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Migel in 3rd graf is cq, according to sheriff's report</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gang members crashed a teen birthday party,
leaving one man stabbed to death and two others wounded, as weekend
gang violence in Southern California claimed a total of four lives
and wounded five.
   Several local gang members crashed a 16th-birthday party for two
girls in West Valinda late Saturday, said Los Angeles County
sheriff's Deputy Dan Cox.
   A fight broke out in the street and Migel Cruz, 21, was fatally
stabbed in the chest, Cox said. Two brothers who were friends of
the hosts were treated for wounds and released from a hospital.
   Elsewhere, gang members in a car mistook six youths in another
car for rivals early Saturday in Lennox and chased them through
several neighborhoods, firing several shots along the way,
sheriff's Lt. Ron Herbst said.
   Two parting shots were fired even when the fleeing youths
reached the door of the sheriff's station in the area 10 miles
south of downtown.
   ``They were scared but not hurt,'' Herbst said.
   A description of the attackers' car was broadcast and a few
minutes later Inglewood police stopped the car and arrested a
14-year-old boy. Other occupants of the stolen car got away.
   Elsewhere, a reputed gang member was wounded in a drive-by
shooting at Lincoln Park early Sunday after an argument between two
groups, police Detective Robert Suter said. Two young men were
being sought.
   The young man was in extremely critical condition at County-USC
Medical Center, Suter said.
   In an attack in Lincoln Heights, another alleged gang member was
shot several times and died at County-USC Medical Center, Suter
said.
   One man was killed and another wounded in a gang-related
shooting late Saturday in Koreatown, police said. Several men were
drinking beer on a porch when the occupants of two cars driving by
shouted gang slogans, then opened fire, Sgt. Alan Bollinger said.
   Late Friday, a 21-year-old man was killed while driving in the
south-central area of the city when three or four young men in a
sedan pulled alongside and yelled a gang slogan, said Deputy Roger
Hom.
   After a brief exchange, someone in the sedan fired several
shots. The man was hit in the chest and died at Martin Luther King
Jr.-Drew Medical Center.
   Three men in a vehicle matching the description of the gunman's
car were stopped and taken in for questioning. There were no
immediate arrests.
   Earlier Friday night, a fight between rival gangs at a Fairfax
High School football game escalated into a street shooting in which
a passenger on a passing motorcycle was wounded. She was in stable
condition at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center with a gunshot wound to
the neck, police said.
   The gang members later shot at a pedestrian on a nearby street,
but missed, said Sgt. Robert Warden. There were no arrests.
</TEXT>
