<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Grenada-Anniversary     10-23 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grenada-Anniversary,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grenada Leader Recalls Strife Leading to U.S.-led Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Grenada Retrospective, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISTER HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGES, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Herbert Blaize told
his countrymen Sunday never to repeat the ``bitter fratricidal
upheaval'' that brought a U.S.-led invasion of this tiny Caribbean
island five years ago.
   ``Eagles do not pay attention to flies,'' Blaize said in a
message marking the invasion. ``Like the eagles, Grenadians should
soar above petty squabbles and individual differences, should try
to understand and help each other, and together concentrate on the
solution of their problems.''
   The prime minister's message recalled the events of Oct. 19,
1983, at army headquarters at Fort George, then known as Fort
Rupert.
   Then Prime Minister Maurice Bishop had been put under house
arrest on Oct. 13 during a power struggle within his leftist
government, but six days later a crowd of thousands marched to his
house and freed him.
   Bishop and some followers went to Fort Rupert, where army troops
in three armored vehicles attacked them with mortars and automatic
weapons.
   Bishop, some members of his Cabinet and others were lined up
against a wall and shot. About 50 people were killed.
   ``We were the targets of the guns in a war among brothers,''
Blaize said in a message read at all of the churches of this
133-square-mile island about 100 miles north of Venezuela. ``We
shot and killed our own parents and brothers, devastated our land
and wasted our property. We pray God that never again should we be
subjected to such cruel experience and wasteful carnage.''
   On Oct. 25, the United States invaded Grenada along with
military units from from seven Caribbean nations. Eighteen
Americans, 45 Grenadans and 29 Cubans were killed during the
fighting.
   In 1984 Blaize helped form the New National Party, which won
parliamentary elections later that year. It was the first elected
government in Grenada since 1979.
   In his message Sunday, Blaize said confrontation is the route
most likely to lead to national catastrophe.
   ``We should always keep in mind that the path of confrontation
will sooner or later bring about self-annihilation for the whole
nation, as was so poignantly demonstrated five years ago,'' he said.
</TEXT>
