<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1757EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CadetsStricken     10-23 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Stricken,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Academy Director Defends His Actions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of training at a police academy where
16 cadets were hospitalized for dehydration and exhaustion says he
wouldn't do anything differently, given what he knew at the time.
   State Trooper Charles B. Gilmore, 31, defended the academy's
training regimen and his own conduct two months ago, saying he
urged the cadets to drink plenty of water and that he reduced their
exercise schedules.
   Gilmore said he thinks daily of Timothy Shepard, 25, the police
recruit who collapsed while running around a track, went into a
coma and required a liver transplant.
   ``I feel bad for Tim Shepard, and I feel for his family,''
Gilmore said. ``There isn't a day that goes by that I don't think
about him. But I look back, and with what I knew, I wouldn't have
done anything differently. There was no detection of anything going
wrong until he went down on the track.''
   Gilmore said he was not responsible for screening candidates for
the Criminal Justice Training Center in Agawam, which trains police
officers for cities and towns in western Massachusetts.
   He had assumed that the entrance requirements were the same as
for the state Police Academy in Framingham, he said. It was not
until three days into the training course that another officer,
Cpl. William Coulter, reviewed the pre-screening material and found
that only 20 of the 50 cadets in the class were in good enough
shape to cope, Gilmore said.
   Gilmore also said he never received a 1985 memo from the
Criminal Justice Training Council urging moderate exercise and
banning some aspects of so-called stress training.
   Many states have abandoned stress training, which is intended to
produce anxiety and confusion through unclear orders, verbal abuse,
sudden actions, humiliating discipline and other pressures.
   ``There has been a civilization of police training, but
(Massachusetts) is a real dinosaur situation. It is really a
shocking perversion,'' said George Kirkham, a criminologist at
Florida State University.
   ``Massachusetts is an anachronism when it comes to law
enforcement. It's 40 years behind the times,'' added Los Angeles
Deputy Police Chief Louis Reiter. ``You could never show that this
kind of training makes a better police officer.''
   But Gilmore defended stress training, saying it prepares
officers for the high-stress situations they face on the job.
   After the controversy erupted over the illnesses of the cadets,
Gilmore voluntarily requested reassignment from the training center
to the state police academy. The center is under investigation by
Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
