<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeaponsProtest     10-23 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weapons Protest,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Crew Involved In Protester's Maiming Blasts Navy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of a freight train say they feel
they've been abandoned by the government since their train ran over
the legs of a protester who sat on railroad tracks outside the
Concord Naval Weapons Station.
   ``Even though we do work for the Navy and I should not say this,
we have not received any public support from the Navy, and that is
something I am very bitter about,'' brakeman Bob Mayfield said
Saturday at a rally near the base about 35 miles east of San
Francisco.
   About 40 people turned out at the event, set up to raise money
and public support for the crew's defense against a lawsuit filed
by maimed protester S. Brian Willson, who lost both lower legs.
   Crew attorney Bill Kolin said the government originally offered
to pay defense attorneys, but at lower than average rates. Now the
government refuses to pay anything, he said.
   A three-man, civilian crew was operating the train Sept. 1,
1987, when Willson and others sat on the tracks to protest arms
shipments to Central America. Willson was the only demonstrator
seriously hurt.
   Since the incident, Mayfield, engineer David A. Humiston and
conductor Ralph Dawson have not returned to work and meet weekly
with a psychologist.
   They say they were not warned that protesters planned to block
the train, although base officials knew about it in advance.
   ``It was a terrible accident and I hate that he had to suffer
like he did, but the fact remains that he is not the only one
suffering,'' said Dawson.
   During the Saturday rally, the arms shipment protest continued
nearby.
   Demonstrator Diane Poole said the crew's superiors knew the
protesters were on the tracks and the crew was ``guilty of
following orders.''
   ``I was deeply moved from what the train crew said, and I feel a
lot of personal empathy for them,'' Poole said. ``I've seen a lot
of lies, but not from the train crew.''
   Willson has spent the last year speaking out against U.S.
intervention in Central America.
</TEXT>
