<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Jaruzelski     10-23 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Jaruzelski,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leader Says Force Could be Used to Maintain Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
said in a speech made public Sunday that authorities will not
hesitate to use force if needed to protect the nation's communist
system.
   He also called on the opposition to avoid ``extreme'' elements.
   Jaruzelski said union pluralism can be allowed in Poland only
when the economy is improved and alternative political forms are
created so that unions do not serve as vehicles for political
demands.
   ``I am aware that no Polish problem can be solved in the long
run by force. Reaching for it is an extreme measure _ although the
hand will not shake if there are attempts at destabilization and an
overthrow of the socialist state,'' he said.
   ``But our force should be first of all in facts and arguments,''
he added, and the success of economic policies will determine the
extent of public support for the authorities.
   Jaruzelski spoke Friday in Warsaw to a meeting of 500
pro-government workers from around the country. Excerpts of the
speech were not made public until Sunday.
   There was a wave of strikes in August with workers demanding
that the outlawed Solidarity union be legalized. Solidarity,
chartered by the government during strikes in 1980, was suspended
in December 1981 and subsequently declared illegal.
   The strikes last August ended when the government promised to
hold round-table talks with the opposition that could include the
topic of Solidarity's future.
   Both sides have said they want the talks to start as soon as
possible and have blamed the other for delays.
   Jaruzelski, head of the Polish United Workers (Communist) Party,
said both political and economic conditions must be right for union
pluralism.
   His party has said a strong economy is needed if Solidarity is
to be legalized, because legalization would set off a ``bidding
war'' of economic demands between Solidarity and the existing
official unions.
   Jaruzelski said other conditions for union pluralism are that
all partners to discussions in Poland recognize the country will
remain part of the Soviet bloc, that there could not be foreign
financial support for Solidarity and that Solidarity avoid
extremist and anti-communist forces.
</TEXT>
