<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hungary-Demonstration     10-23 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Demonstration,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Several Hundred Commemorate Anti-Communist Uprising, Five Detained</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred people on Sunday defied
an official ban and demonstrated to commemorate the 1956
anti-communist uprising. Five were detained, an official report
said.
   The demonstrators toured city landmarks while about 4,000 riot
police patroled around the sites important to the revolt, according
to opposition activist Ferenc Koeszeg. He said there was no
violence.
   The official MTI news agency said five people were detained
because they refused to provide identification, lacked proper
documents, or made ``offensive statements.''
   Koeszeg identified two arrested demonstrators as Tibor Pakh and
Robert Palinkas. He said police took Pakh away as he was trying to
address a crowd and removed Palinkas as he carried a bouquet of
flowers tied by white, green and red ribbons _ the national colors.
   The demonstrators were marking the anniversary of the start of
the uprising, the bloodiest ever against Soviet control in East
bloc nations.
   As the revolt flared a new coalition government under Premier
Imre Nagy declared the country neutral and withdrew from the
Soviet-controlled Warsaw Treaty organization.
   But Janos Kadar, one of Nagy's ministers, declared his own
government and asked the Soviet Union for military support. Soviet
forces moved in and crushed the revolt, and Nagy and some of his
ministers were executed.
   Kadar became premier and nearly 200,000 Hungarians fled the
country. Sunday's demonstrators gathered for their memorial tour
even though authorities on Friday imposed a ban on any such event.
Koeszeg said an unofficial march was canceled by independent
groups, but its organizers decided to take to the streets after
learning that some people intended to defy the ban.
   
   One group that went to the Bem statue in Budapest, where the
uprising began, was turned back. The statue was encircled by police
who checked identification papers.
</TEXT>
