<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NicaraguanInflux     10-23 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaraguan Influx,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Nicaraguans Pour into Miami Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Nicaraguans fleeing their war-torn and
economically ravaged homeland are coming to Dade County, and the
influx is straining social services, hospitals and schools,
officials said.
   The Central American nation's economy is worsening, and U.S. aid
to Contra rebels has been curtailed, leaving a bleak future for
many Nicaraguans. Heavily Latin Dade County, which includes Miami,
is a natural destination.
   As many as 300 Nicaraguans a week have been arriving in recent
months, said Perry Rivkind, district director of the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   In 1980, most of the 125,000 Cubans who came to Florida in the
Mariel boat lift settled in Dade County, along with tens of
thousands of Haitians. The sudden influx caused severe social
problems. Local officials are now concerned that a similar
situation could develop with the Nicaraguans.
   ``It's going to be another Mariel,'' said Rosario Kennedy,
Miami's vice mayor. ``We've got to do something.''
   Most Nicaraguans are in a legal limbo, and county and state
officials can't obtain the federal aid that helped the county cope
with the Cubans and Haitians.
   ``Call them entrants, call them refugees, call them whatever you
want,'' but the federal government must do something, said Bobby
Bernal, county aide for refugee affairs. ``Because they will
continue to come.''
   The county said most of the estimated 75,000 to 100,000
Nicaraguans in the county didn't qualify for the federal amnesty
offered earlier this year to illegal aliens who arrived before
1982. INS has granted 5,000 of the 50,000 requests for political
asylym sought by Nicaraguans.
   The INS is issuing work permits to asylum applicants, and the
Reagan administration has decided not to deport non-criminal
Nicaraguans, even if they are here illegally. But they do not
qualify for federally funded programs such as food stamps or job
training.
   In the last three months, more Nicaraguan children have enrolled
in local schools than at any time since the 1979 leftist Sandinista
revolution, said Ralph Robinett, executive director of the Dade
School system's bilingual and and foreign education.
   From July to September, 1,653 Nicaraguans registered for the
first time, pushing their total past 10,000 in Dade schools. Many
of the students are poorly educated and need extra help.
   ``They need to have a lot of remedial help,'' Robinett said. The
schools' bilingual program isn't geared to deal with remedial needs
but instead assumes students are fluent in Spanish.
   Private efforts are being overburdened. The Nicaraguan
Assistance Center is falling behind on its bills and charity
funding is down, officials say.
   ``We do what we can,'' said the Rev. Francisco Santana, whose
Sweetwater parish, Our Lady of Divine Providence, is often a first
stop for Nicaraguans. ``But I don't know how long we can stand it.
Christianity says we can't turn them away. But the numbers are such
that we can't help them all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
