<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UndercoverMom 1stLd-Writethru a0794 10-23 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Undercover Mom, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0794,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Undercover Mom Lives in Fear</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with four grafs to add that arrests made Wednesday, and
Morrison's comments made Saturday and adds her age.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who went undercover to help police
arrest the six men who were supplying her daughters with drugs says
the two are not speaking to her anymore.
   Pat Morrison, 44, also says her roommate has asked her to move,
and that she lives in fear of the people arrested Wednesday after
her work for the Dallas, Ore., Police Department.
   In spite of it all, Morrison, a mother of four and grandmother
of two, says she has no regrets. She wanted to help her grown
daughters get off drugs, and she did the only thing she could think
of _ she infiltrated the group that allegedly supplied her
daughters with drugs from a methamphetamine lab.
   ``I gave it a lot of thought because I didn't want to get the
girls in trouble,'' she said Saturday. ``I don't want 'em to have a
record ... but I kept thinking of what (drugs were) doing to my
girls.''
   Morrison said she tried the drug herself a couple of times,
mixing it with milk to disguise the smell and taste. But she didn't
like what it did to her.
   Worse yet, she was terrified by the grip drugs had on her
daughters, aged 21 and 24, who were living in their cars and
selling drugs to support their habits.
   In desperation, Morrison called authorities and offered to give
them information about the suppliers. They agreed, and Morrison
soon was making daily treks to the five-acre farm where her
daughters bought drugs.
   At first, she pretended to be looking for her daughters. Before
long, people began feeling relaxed, and eventually they started to
open up, she said.
   As they talked about their operation they didn't guess that
their words were being picked up by detectives hiding in a nearby
motor home. Morrison was recording conversations through a hidden
microphone.
   Morrison said that while she was afraid of the group, she grew
to like the friendly, quiet people at the farm.
   ``There toward the end, it was really hard to do what I did,''
she said of the two-week project.
   Morrison figured the matter would be closed once the arrests
were complete, but reports of her mission stirred media interest.
   Since then, she has had calls from a book publisher and TV movie
producers.
   Though Morrison would like to tell about her experiences, right
now she says she has more pressing problems.
   Her 3-year-old granddaughter, Aquila, needs her attention. Her
16-year-old car has broken down. And her roommate left a note for
her Saturday, asking Morrison to move because the woman fears for
her safety.
   The police are keeping an eye on Morrison, who is concerned for
her safety because four of the six men have been released on bail.
   And though her daughters are hardly speaking to her, she is
hopeful they will understand someday.
   ``I didn't know if it would help, but I had to try,'' said
Morrison. ``The police cannot do this all by themselves. Why don't
people do something about (drugs), instead of just sitting home
worrying about (them)?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 2015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0756 10-23 1008</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0756,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen, Jackson Say Race Underlies GOP's Prison Furlough Issue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 8th pvs, Asked if..., to say Dukakis
agrees with Bentsen statement; INSERTS two grafs after 12th pvs,
Dukakis made..., to update with Dukakis appearance in Eau Claire</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen and the Rev. Jesse Jackson accused Republican
nominee George Bush's campaign Sunday of injecting racism into the
presidential campaign by pounding Democrat Michael Dukakis over the
Massachusetts prison furlough issue.
   A Bush spokesman said the charge was ``absolutely ridiculous and
stems from desperation politics.''
   Dukakis attended a breakfast in Boston with Jackson and eight
other black political leaders who pledged to support the
Massachusetts governor's campaign in the remaining two weeks before
the Nov. 8 election.
   Then Dukakis flew via Wisconsin to California for a full day of
campaigning Monday for that crucial state's 47 electoral votes.
Bush and his running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, took a
respite from campaigning at their Washington homes.
   The tenor and substance of the GOP ticket's campaign advertising
on television dominated the political dialogue Sunday.
   Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential candidate, told a
television interviewer he thought the Bush campaign was making a
racist appeal by focusing on Willie Horton Jr., a black convicted
murderer who escaped in 1986 from a Massachusetts prison furlough.
   In 1987, Horton brutally stabbed a white Maryland man and twice
raped his fiancee. Horton is currently imprisoned in Maryland.
   Asked if use of the Horton case constituted ``an element of
Republican racist appeal,'' Bentsen replied: ``When you add it up,
I think there is, and that's unfortunate, and I just don't want to
see this election won on that kind of packaging and that kind of
distortions.''
   Dukakis campaign vice chairman John Sasso said Dukakis agreed
with those comments.
   In Boston, Jackson avoided the word ``racist'' but said the
Horton case was one of several ``rather ugly race-conscious
signals'' sent out by the Bush campaign.
   ``There have been a number of rather blatantly race-conscious
signals that have had the impact of instilling ungrounded fear in
whites and alientation from blacks,'' Jackson told reporters after
the 90-minute breakfast with Dukakis.
   ``The use of the Willie Horton example is designed to create the
most horrible psycho-sexual fears,'' Jackson said. ``The furlough
ad with black and brown faces rotating in and out of jail, the use
of the Jackson-Dukakis ticket symbolism, which is distortion,
referring to me as a Chicago hustler ... there have been a number
of rather ugly race-conscious signals sent from that campaign.''
   Dukakis made no mention of the prison furlough issue in a short
statement after the breakfast. He said only that it had been a
``good, constructive meeting'' and that he was pleased by the black
leaders' commitment to his campaign.
   But at an airport rally in Eau Claire, Wis., Dukakis said Bush's
disavowal of a brochure being distributed in Michigan that says
Massachusetts convicts are voting for Dukakis was an inadequate
response.
   ``Disavowal isn't enough,'' Dukakis told the crowd of about 500
people. ``Let's get that stuff out of this campaign.''
   Bush campaign spokesman Mark Goodin said that for Bentsen and
Jackson ``to insinuate that the furlough issue has racial overtones
is absolutely ridiculous and stems from desperation politics.''
   Goodin said the GOP campaign's television commercials focused
not on Horton but on ``how he got out of prison.'' He said
correctly that Massachusetts granted furloughs to convicted
first-degree murderers serving life without the possibility of
parole. That policy was rescinded last spring.
   ``To insinuate that racism is involved in the furlough issue
operates from the ridiculous premise that black citizens care less
about having a monster in their neighborhoods like Willie Horton
than do white people,'' Goodin said.
   ``That is totally incorrect and an outrageous suggestion,'' he
said. ``Anyone who makes it should be ashamed of themselves.''
   Bentsen, interviewed on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David
Brinkley,'' said if Bush wins on the basis of such a campaign, ``I
think that'd be a tragedy, and I think that's one of the reasons
the American people will turn against them, with that kind of
campaign, and that's why I think we're going to put it all
together.''
   On the same TV program, Senate Minority Leader Robert Dole,
R-Kan., a former Bush opponent in the GOP primaries, also was asked
if the Bush campaign's Willie Horton ads were racially motivated.
   ``I don't think that's the case,'' he replied, but then added:
``I'm not involved in the Bush campaign. I can defend George Bush,
but I'm not sure I can defend every ad.''
   Kitty Dukakis, the Democratic nominee's wife, appeared on
CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation'' to say her husband had
``underestimated how vitriolic, how vicious, how negative those
false attacks were'' by the Bush campaign.
   She said some of the Bush campaign charges reminded her of the
``worst kind of McCarthy-like technique'' from the
communist-hunting 1950s, and of the dirty tricks of President
Nixon's election campaigns.
   On NBC's ``Meet the Press'' program, Charles Black, media
consultant for the Bush campaign, denied that his colleagues are
running a ``dirty campaign.'' Black said that ``we've presented
assertions and facts that are all documented and that are all
true.''
   Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk said on the same program
that the Bush TV advertising campaign ``has been unprecedented in
terms of the politics of deception, deliberate distortion,
distraction from the issues that the American people are facing in
the 1990s, and disguised behind labels.''
   In other developments, a new poll conducted for the Dallas
Morning News and the Houston Chronicle showed that the Bush-Quayle
ticket led the Dukakis-Bentsen ticket among likely Texas voters by
52 percent to 42 percent.
   If Bush were pitted only against Dukakis, without regard for
their vice presidential running mates, Bush led Dukakis by 56
percent to 40 percent, according to the survey of 776 potential
voters conducted between Oct. 17 and Oct. 20.
   The poll had a margin of error of plus or minus four percentage
points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 2033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bluefields     10-23 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bluefields,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivors Share Food Amidst Ruins of Shattered City</HEAD>
<HEAD>with AM-Joan-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO TAPIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLUEFIELDS, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frightened dogs watched from the
roofless ruins of houses Sunday as thousands of people who survived
Hurricane Joan set up makeshift shelters, cleared streets and
shared their food.
   Bluefields had been celebrating its 85th anniversary with a fair
that included dancing, gambling and reggae music when warnings of
the impending hurricane began. Few believed it would be as bad as
it was.
   During the height of the storm at 3 a.m. Saturday roofs and
downed trees went flying through the air, pounded into buildings by
125 mph winds.
   As the hurricane subsided after dawn, dazed people began
appearing in the streets _ soldiers carrying elderlyn, women
carrying their children, girls carrying dolls.
   The number of buildings that still had their roofs could be
counted on the fingers of two hands: The Hotel Caribe, the radio
station, the Colombian consulate, the jail, the Moravian college
and the Roman Catholic cathedral _ part of it.
   ``Now nobody can laugh at us,'' said one impoverished survivor
in tattered clothes. ``Nobody has anything.''
   The new City Hall, dedicated only last week during the
anniversary celebration, was reduced to a roofless skeleton. So was
the Moravian church near the harbor.
   Streets were littered with the bodies of parrots, rats, bats and
dogs.
   Despite the destruction only 21 people perished in Bluefields,
said William Ramirez, a Sandinista Party official in charge of
recovery efforts. He said there were many injuries but few were
serious.
   The city, with a population of 38,000, may have been saved by
its bay, which protected it from the huge waves and tremendous
storm surge that is usually the most serious killer in hurricanes.
   The only communications with the outside were via government
radio. Telephones were out and no roads penetrate the jungle that
surrounds Bluefields.
   Authorities drafted prisoners to help clear the road to the
airport. The first relief flight from Cuba arrived shortly after
noon Sunday carrying doctors.
   Many neighborhoods in this city, populated mainly by blacks and
Indians, have American names: Brooklyn, Harlem, New York. In many
of those poor neighborhoods not one house was left standing.
   ``There isn't enough left of the houses to make a fire,'' said a
Red Cross nurse.
   There were the unlucky ones. A fishing boat that tried to escape
up a flooded river sank, killing a woman and her two children. Two
women who took shelter in the Anglican church perished when it
collapsed.
   But there was no panic, except among the children, at the height
of the storm, according to Ramirez.
   ``The people of Bluefields are valiant and never were afraid,''
he said.
   People shared what food they had. Many fishing boats were
destroyed, but others were being repaired.
   Ramirez said many people have relatives in the United States and
called on them for help. When asked what was needed, he said: ``We
need everything.''
   Nicaragua recently passed a law banning aid from the United
States to enter the country because of U.S. support for rebels, but
Ramirez said President Daniel Ortega had authorized help for
Bluefields from any part of the world.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Editor's Note _ Mario Tapia, a photographer for The Associated
Press, was in Bluefields when the hurricane struck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
