<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrideII     10-23 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pride II,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pride II Departs On Maiden Voyage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The clipper schooner Pride of Baltimore II
departed on its maiden voyage Sunday, more than two years after the
original Pride sank in a sudden storm, killing four crew members.
   Like its predecessor, the vessel is modeled after those that
sailed the Chesapeake Bay in the 19th century and will visit other
cities and foreign countries as Maryland's and Baltimore's goodwill
ambassador.
   In order to meet U.S. Coast Guard safety requirements for
carrying passengers, Pride II is almost one-third larger than the
original Pride and 64 tons heavier. Unlike the first Pride, it is
equipped with a second diesel motor, separate compartments for its
12 crew members, and a modern kitchen.
   At Capt. Jan Miles' order, the crew hoisted a replica of the
15-star, 15-stripe U.S. flag that is believed to have flown over
nearby Fort McHenry during the War of 1812; the flag that tradition
holds was still flying and inspired Francis Scott Key to pen the
national anthem.
   The U.S. flag was quickly joined by the flags of Maryland and
Baltimore and a Pride of Baltimore II pennant.
   A shot was fired from a replica of a 19th century cannon on the
starboard side, and the clipper schooner pulled away. It sailed
around the harbor with all five sails unfurled as thousands of
people watched from the shore. A small armada of about 50 private
boats followed the vessel for about an hour until it sailed past
Fort McHenry and under the Francis Scott Key Bridge.
   Before it returns to Baltimore April 21, the clipper schooner is
scheduled to travel to Bermuda; Houston and Galveston, Texas; New
Orleans; Mobile, Ala.; Tampa, Fla.; Puerto Rico, Venezuela,
Colombia, Miami, Jacksonville, Fla.; Savannah, Ga.; North and South
Carolina; and Norfolk, Va.
   It was built with $4 million in donations and government money.
   The vessel was christened April 30, in memory of the captain and
three crew members who died when the Pride sank May 14, 1986, when
a sudden squall blew up 90 miles off the coast of Puerto Rico. The
eight survivors clung to a life raft for five days, rationed to a
bite of biscuit and a half cup of water daily.
   None of the original crew sailed with the Pride II on Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
