<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 2237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-MichaelJackson     10-23 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Michael Jackson,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michael Jackson Visits Museum</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Jackson visited the modest house where
Berry Gordy Jr. launched Motown and donated $125,000 Sunday for
preservation of the sound that's as much a part of Detroit as
automobiles.
   Jackson, making a rare public appearance, toured the Motown
Museum with Gordy, who called the pop superstar one of the museum's
greatest supporters.
   ``Michael Jackson knows success in life is not merely confined
to fame and fortune and material gains, but it's also found in a
continual awareness of our roots, his roots,'' said Gordy, who
founded Motown in 1959, moved it to Los Angeles in 1972 and sold it
to MCA Records for $61 million last June.
   ``These are Michael Jackson's roots, right here.''
   At least 2,500 people cheered wildly from behind a fence about
60 yards away from the museum when Jackson stepped to the
microphone.
   ``I'm very happy and proud to be back to the soil from which I
came,'' Jackson said. ``Berry Gordy is the man that made it all
possible for me. I want to say thank you, Berry, and I love you.''
   The fans endured a constant, cold rain to get a glimpse of
Jackson, who is scheduled to perform two shows this week at the
Palace of Auburn Hills.
   Motown Records recorded the music of Diana Ross and The
Supremes, Stevie Wonder, Smokey Robinson, Lionel Richie and other
Motown stars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
