<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--CruiserLaunched     10-23 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cruiser Launched,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Weather Delay, Aegis Cruiser is Launched</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATH, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bath Iron Works Corp. on Sunday launched the
fourth Aegis cruiser the shipbuilding company has built for the
U.S. Navy.
   The Monterey had been scheduled to slide down the ways on
Saturday, but heavy rain forced officials to postpone the launching.
   Capt. Joel B. Heaton, prospective commanding officer of the
ship, was presented a flag that had flown aboard the previous naval
vessel Monterey, which won 11 battle stars during service in the
Pacific during World War II.
   The new, 567-foot Monterey will carry a crew of 375 when
commissioned into the Navy's active fleet in early 1990.
   Aboard the $1-billion cruiser, which may be assigned to an
aircraft carrier battle group, is an advanced system of radar,
computers and missiles called Aegis. The word comes from the Greek
for ``shield.''
   Bath Iron Works has seven Aegis cruisers under contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
