<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 0134EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-APElectionService 1stadd   10-23 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Election Service, 1st add,640,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: of Columbia.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here's the Republican ticket at a glance:
   
   GEORGE HERBERT WALKER BUSH, the presidential candidate.
   Current office _ Bush is vice president of the United States.
   Personal, family _ Bush was born June 12, 1924, in Milton,
Mass.; lived in Grenwich, Conn., and Houston, Texas. His parents:
Prescott Bush and Dorothy Walker Bush. Prescott Bush was a U.S.
senator from Connecticut, 1952-63. George Bush and his wife, the
former Barbara Pierce, have five children _ George, Jeb, Neil,
Marvin, and Dorothy.
   Education, military service _ Bush graduated from Phillips
Academy in Andover, Mass., in 1942. He was in the Navy, 1942-45. He
went to Yale University, receiving a bachelor's degree in economics
in 1948.
   Occupations _ In 1951, he co-founded a small royalty firm. He
co-founded Zapata Petroleum Corp. in 1953. In 1954, he co-founded
and became president of Zapata Off-Shore Co., which sold drilling
equipment.
   Election history _ Bush was elected to the U.S. House in 1966 to
represent a Texas district, began congressional service Jan. 3,
1967; was re-elected in 1968; did not seek re-election to the House
in 1970, and left office Jan. 3, 1971. He ran unsuccessfully in
Texas for the U.S. Senate, as the Republican nominee, in 1964 and
1970. He unsuccessfully sought the Republican presidential
nomination in 1980, and later became Ronald Reagan's running mate.
He was elected vice president on the ticket with Reagan in 1980,
taking office Jan. 20, 1981. Reagan and Bush were re-elected in
1984. Bush announced his 1988 presidential candidacy on Oct. 12,
1987. In the AP delegate count during the primary and caucus
season, he locked up the nomination April 27. He was nominated at
the Republican convention in New Orleans Aug. 17, without
opposition; he received all 2,277 votes.
   Other posts _ Bush was U.S. ambassador to the United Nations
under President Richard M. Nixon, 1971-73. He was chairman of the
Republican National Committee, 1973-74. He was chief of the U.S.
Liaison Office in China, 1974-75. He was director of the Central
Intelligence Agency, 1976-77, appointed by President Gerald R. Ford.
   
   JAMES DANFORTH QUAYLE, the vice presidential candidate.
   Current office _ Quayle is a U.S. senator from Indiana.
   Personal, family _ Quayle was born Feb. 4, 1947, in
Indianapolis, Ind.; lived in Huntington, Ind. His parents: James C.
Quayle, publisher of the Huntington Herald-Press, and Corinne P.
Quayle. Dan Quayle's grandfather, Eugene C. Pulliam, was a
newspaper publisher in Indiana and Arizona. Dan Quayle and his
wife, the former Marilyn Tucker, have three children _ Tucker,
Benjamin and Corinne.
   Education, military service _ Quayle graduated from Huntington
High School in 1965. He was educated at DePauw University, getting
a bachelor's degree in political science in 1969, and received a
law degree from Indiana University Law School in 1974. He was in
the Indiana National Guard, 1969-75.
   Occupations _ Quayle was an investigator for the Indiana
attorney general, a gubernatorial aide, and director of the
inheritance tax division of the Indiana Department of Revenue. He
practiced law. He was associate publisher of the Huntington
Herald-Press.
   Election history _ Quayle was elected to the U.S. House in 1976,
ousting eight-term Democrat J. Edward Roush. Quayle began
congressional service Jan. 3, 1977. He was re-elected to the House
in 1978. Instead of seeking a third House term, Quayle ran in 1980
for the U.S. Senate and ousted Democrat Birch E. Bayh Jr., who had
been a senator since Jan. 3, 1963. Quayle began Senate service Jan.
3, 1981. He was re-elected to the Senate in 1986. Bush selected
Quayle to be his vice presidential running mate this year and
Quayle was nominated by acclamation at the GOP national convention
Aug. 18.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 0135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-APElectionService 2ndadd   10-23 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Election Service, 2nd add,700,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: Aug. 18.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here's the Democratic ticket at a glance:
   
   MICHAEL STANLEY DUKAKIS, the presidential candidate.
   Current office _ Dukakis is governor of Massachusetts.
   Personal, family _ Dukakis was born Nov. 3, 1933; in Brookline,
Mass. His parents: Panos Dukakis and Euterpe Boukis Dukakis, Greek
immigrants. Michael Dukakis and his wife, the former Katharine
Dickson, have three children _ John, Andrea and Kara.
   Education, military service _ Dukakis went to Brookline High
School, receiving his diploma in 1951. He was educated at
Swarthmore College, gaining a bachelor's degree in political
science in 1955, and got a law degree from Harvard Law School in
1960. He was in the Army, 1955-57, serving in Korea.
   Occupations _ Dukakis practiced law. He was a moderator of
public television's ``The Advocates,'' 1971-73. He was a lecturer
and director of intergovernmental studies at Harvard's John F.
Kennedy School of Government, 1979-82.
   Election history _ Dukakis was first elected to the
Massachusetts House in 1962, serving there 1963-71. He lost a 1970
attempt to become lieutenant governor of Massachusetts. He was
elected governor of Massachusetts in 1974, and lost a bid for
Democratic renomination in 1978, serving in the office from Jan. 2,
1975, to Jan. 4, 1979. He again was elected governor in 1982,
returning to office Jan. 6, 1983, and was re-elected in 1986 for a
term expiring in 1991. He announced his 1988 candidacy for the
presidency on April 29, 1987. In the AP delegate count during the
1988 primary and caucus season, he locked up the nomination June 7.
He was nominated at the Democratic convention in Atlanta July 20,
defeating the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson. The tally was 2,876.25
delegate votes for Dukakis, 1,218.5 for Jackson, and 9 for others.
Then, Jackson, in a unity gesture, released his delegates and the
convention agreed by voice vote to make it unanimous for Dukakis.
   
   LLOYD MILLARD BENTSEN JR., the vice presidential candidate.
   Current office _ Bentsen is a U.S. senator from Texas.
   Personal, family _ Bentsen was born Feb. 11, 1921, in Mission,
Texas; lived in Starr County. His great-great-uncle was Henry
Wilson, vice president in 1873-75 during President Ulysses S.
Grant's second administration. Bentsen's father, Lloyd Sr., a son
of Danish immigrants, was a rancher who started with little money
and built a financial dynasty in land. Lloyd Bentsen Jr. and his
wife, the former Beryl Ann Longino, have three children _ Lloyd M.
III, Lan Chase, and Tina Ann.
   Education, military service _ Bentsen was educated at the
University of Texas, receiving a law degree in 1942. He was in the
Army in World War II.
   Occupations _ He practiced law. He was a business executive in
Houston, 1955-72. He headed Lincoln Consolidated, a financial
holding institution.
   Election history _ Bentsen was elected a judge of Hidalgo
County, Texas, in 1946. He was elected in November 1948 to the U.S.
Hose for the 81st Congress, then was elected the next month to
serve for the rest of the 80th Congress. That December special
election filled a vacancy in the 80th Congress caused by the death
of an incumbent who didn't run for the 81st Congress. Thus, Bentsen
began congressional service Dec. 4, 1948. He was re-elected in 1950
and 1952. He did not run again in 1954, leaving office in 1955. He
was elected to the U.S. Senate in 1970, starting service Jan. 3,
1971; and was re-elected in 1976 and 1982. He ran this year for a
new term, gaining Democratic renomination at the March 8 primary.
Bentsen announced his candidacy for the presidency on Feb. 17,
1975, and dropped out of the national race for the Democratic
nomination Feb. 10, 1976, while remaining a favorite-son candidate
in Texas. He lost to Jimmy Carter in that Texas test in May 1976.
This year, Dukakis selected Bentsen to be his vice presidential
running mate and Bentsen was nominated by acclamation at the
Democratic national convention July 21. Texas law allows Bentsen to
run both for vice president and for re-election to the Senate this
year.
</TEXT>
