<HEAD>UNDATED: of Columbia.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   The run for the White House is actually 51 races throughout the
nation on Election Day.
   In 1984, Republican Ronald Reagan, a 49-state winner, and
Democrat Walter Mondale, second everywhere except in Minnesota and
Washington, D.C., were the top two finishers nationally and Reagan
easily retained the presidency.
   They received the majority of popular votes cast in the
individual elections in 50 states and the District of Columbia but
they didn't get them all because other candidates drew some support
here and there.
   Among those who also ran for the presidency in 1984, David
Bergland of the Libertarian Party came in third nationally with
227,204 votes.
   In detail, according to official statistics published by
Congress, here are the popular votes for Reagan and Mondale in
those 51 elections, and their percentage of the total vote for all
candidates in these races.
</TEXT>
