<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Election Service, 22nd add,930,0931</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: Senate wing.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   24. RHODE ISLAND _ Republican John H. Chafee, of Warwick, was
born Oct. 22, 1922.
   First elected: 1976.
   Began serving: Dec. 29, 1976.
   Election history: In 1976, Chafee, a former three-term Rhode
Island governor who lost his 1968 gubernatorial re-election race,
finally won a Senate seat. It was his second attempt to join the
Senate and yet another in a series of election races for Chafee.
After serving in the Rhode Island Legislature, he was elected
governor in 1962, unseating Democrat John A. Notte Jr. Chafee won
by just 398 votes out of 327,506 cast. He then picked up new
two-year terms in 1964 and 1966, but failed when he reached for No.
4 in 1968. Shortly after that gubernatorial election loss to
Democrat Frank Licht, Chafee went to Washington to join the Nixon
administration as Navy secretary. After serving in that post from
January 1969 to May 1972, he returned to Rhode Island and tried to
knock Democrat Claiborne Pell out of the Senate in 1972. Chafee
lost that election to Pell by 32,952 votes out of more than 413,400
cast. When Democrat John O. Pastore, a senator since Dec. 19, 1950,
decided to retire instead of running anew in 1976, Chafee was
elected with 57.7 percent of the vote, defeating Democrat Richard
P. Lorber, an automobile dealer. After the election, Pastore
resigned and the governor appointed Chafee to serve the last days
of Pastore's term. Chafee was re-elected in 1982, drawing 51.2
percent of the vote in beating Democrat Julius C. Michaelson, a
former Rhode Island attorney general. Chafee won by 8,212 votes out
of nearly 342,800 cast.
   
   
   25. TENNESSEE _ Democrat James R. Sasser, of Nashville, was born
Sept. 30, 1936.
   First elected: 1976.
   Began serving: Jan. 3, 1977.
   Election history: In 1976, Sasser, an attorney making his first
bid for public office after having been long active in Tennessee
Democratic circles, took on Republican Sen. William E. Brock and
defeated him by 77,949 votes out of more than 1.43 million cast.
Brock, heir to a fortune flowing from candy, went on to serve as
GOP national chairman and helped overhaul the party. Sasser became
a critic of President Reagan's economic policies and picked up a
second Senate term with 61.9 percent of the vote. Republicans
offered five-term Congressman Robin L. Beard Jr. as their Senate
candidate in 1982 and he called Sasser a big spender who helped get
``our economy in the shape it is in.'' Sasser claimed Beard ``spent
the entire campaign being negative _ running some of the most
repulsive and misleading political ads'' in history. Out of nearly
1.26 million votes cast, Sasser topped Beard by 300,471.
   
   
   26. TEXAS _ Democrat Lloyd M. Bentsen Jr., of Starr County, was
born Feb. 11, 1921. This year, he was renominated for the Senate at
the Texas Democratic primary March 8. Later, at the Democratic
National Convention July 21, he also was nominated to run for the
vice presidency on the party's national ticket with presidential
nominee Michael S. Dukakis. In such cases, Texas law allows a
candidate to run for both offices at once, just as Lyndon B.
Johnson did in 1960.
   First elected: 1970.
   Began serving: Jan. 3, 1971.
   Election history: In 1970, Bentsen, again riding the Texas
political trail after sitting in the House in 1948-55 and then
giving it all up to be a businessman, upset liberal Sen. Ralph W.
Yarborough in the Democratic primary and grabbed a Senate seat with
53.3 percent of the vote. Bentsen's GOP rival was one George Bush,
a congressman back then, and the voters lined up: 1,226,568 for
Bentsen, 1,071,234 for Bush, 1,808 for others. Flash forward. Bush
is vice president, Bentsen's a Senate power, and they're together
again yet still apart on the ballot: Bush for president, Bentsen
for vice president. Not only that, but what you are about to read
is legal in Texas: It's also Bentsen for Senate again. In 1960,
Lone Star law let Texan Lyndon B. Johnson ride again for the
Senate, and he beat Republican John G. Tower _ and it also let him
share the Democrats' national horse with John F. Kennedy, who rode
up front, when they carried Texas with 50.5 percent of the popular
vote and won the presidency and vice presidency. Johnson became No.
2. That Senate seat he wanted to keep in 1960, just in case the
national horse didn't make it, was given up by him when the horse
came through. And that seat was won by Tower at a 1961 special
election and remains Republican even today, now occupied by Phil
Gramm. Bentsen, after beating Bush in 1970, faced Republican
congressmen each time he wanted six more Senate years. Bentsen won
in 1976, with 56.8 percent of the vote, against Alan Steelman, and
in 1982, with 58.6 percent, against James Collins. This time, it's
another GOP congressman, Beau Boulter, between Bentsen and another
term. And if Bentsen, like Johnson, wins both races, takes the vice
presidency and thus quits as senator, it means Bush didn't win the
White House, is available for other things come Jan. 20, and the
Republican governor must decide what next. Bush for senator? Or
Boulter? Will the governor punt to the voters on first down? Will
he take the ball and hide? Do Texans love this sort of thing? Is
winter hot in Texas? How hot will this one be?
</TEXT>
