<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Election Service, 23rd add,1,100,1098</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: one be?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   27. UTAH _ Republican Orrin G. Hatch, of Salt Lake City, was
born March 22, 1934.
   First elected: 1976.
   Began serving: Jan. 3, 1977.
   Election history: In 1976, Hatch, a lawyer launching his Utah
political career in an impressive way, snapped up 55.6 percent of
the vote and upset Democrat Frank E. Moss, who has been a senator
since Jan. 3, 1959. Hatch, a conservative running as an opponent of
big government and what he branded poor fiscal policies, won the
GOP nomination over Jack Carlson, a former assistant secretary of
the interior. Moss was chairman of what then was the Aeronautical
and Space Sciences Committee and contended he had reached the most
productive part of his Senate career. He said he thought ``that
once having put your hand to the plow, you should continue to the
end of the row.'' But Hatch ran away from Moss at the polls.
Republicans gained control of the Senate with the 1980 elections
and Hatch, still a first-termer, became head of the Labor and Human
Resources Committee. Campaigning from that position of power, Hatch
was unchallenged in the 1982 GOP primary and surged to a second
term against Democrat Ted Wilson, Salt Lake City's mayor, 309,332
votes to 219,482. Hatch had tied himself closely to President
Reagan's economic policy in an appeal to the state's largely
conservative electorate and it paid off in his
stronger-than-expected showing in an expensive race with Wilson.
The tide that returned the Democrats to the Senate majority in the
elections of 1986 also washed away Hatch's chairmanship but he
remained the top Republican on the Labor and Human Resources
Committee.
   
   
   28. VERMONT _ Republican Robert T. Stafford, of Rutland, was
born Aug. 8, 1913. Instead of running again this year, Stafford is
retiring from office. He announced his decision April 10, 1987.
   First elected: 1972.
   Previously appointed: 1971.
   Began serving: Sept. 16, 1971.
   Election history: In 1972, Stafford won a January special
election to keep the seat he had obtained by appointment of the GOP
governor in 1971 to fill a vacancy created by the death of
Republican Winston L. Prouty. By the time he reached the Senate,
Vermont voters knew Stafford well because he had been on their
ballots and won every two years since back in the 1950s. When the
nation was younger and slimmer, Vermont occupied six of the 186
U.S. House seats available based on America's 1810 census. But by
the time Stafford first won a House election in 1960, Vermont had
long ago slipped to the constitutional floor _ it was a single-seat
state. So, when they saw his name, voters cared not whether it was
on the line for governor, U.S. House or U.S. Senate. The real
question was: Do we want to send him where he wants to go?
Stafford's wish and the voters' majority will were one from start
to finish, it was close at times but they always decided to go with
him. Last year, he decided the time had come to retire instead of
running this year. The voters had elected him governor in 1958,
making him No. 1 in Vermont, elected him congressman in 1960, 1962,
1964, 1966, 1968, and 1970, making him one among 435, and elected
him senator in January 1972, approving the GOP governor's decision
to make Stafford one of the 100. When Stafford ran for a full
Senate term in 1976, Democratic Gov. Thomas P. Salmon tried to
unseat him. Stafford won by nearly 8,800 votes out of more than
189,000 cast. Six years later, Stafford had a serious primary test
but was renominated over Stewart M. Ledbetter, a former banking and
insurance commissioner who had been the 1980 GOP Senate nominee.
For the fall, Democrats went with James A. Guest, a former Vermont
secretary of state, and the voters favored Stafford by just over
5,100 votes out of about 168,000 cast. When he announced in 1987
that he would not seek re-election in 1988, Stafford declared:
``There is considerable work still ahead for me. I would only
suggest that the writing of my political obituary be put off until
that work is finished.''
   
   
   29. VIRGINIA _ Republican Paul S. Trible Jr., of Kilmarnock, was
born Dec. 29, 1946. Instead of running again this year, Trible is
retiring from this office. He announced his decision Sept. 19,
1987. On July 30, 1988, Trible declared his candidacy for the
Republican nomination for governor of Virginia in 1989.
   First elected: 1982.
   Began serving: Jan. 3, 1983.
   Election history: In 1982, Trible, a three-term congressman, won
what some old-timers still see as the Byrd seat, the one from
Virginia that passed from father to son, all in the family for 50
years, father resigning due to illness and son retiring after
saying he'd held it ``long enough.'' Trible surprised many by
revealing he wanted out after just six years. Senate life's just
not for me, said Trible, family life, Virginia life, that's my
life. ``For all the Senate's greatness,'' he said, ``much of the
important work of the nation doesn't seem to get done. The
committee hearings, debates, filibusters and roll call votes go on
and on and on. Personally, I want to be better able to shape my
day, set the agenda, do more for my family and for Virginia.'' A
little later, leaving his door ajar to life after the Senate,
Trible said he still enjoys politics and ``I love beating
Democrats.'' Thus, it stunned only a few this year when Trible
declared his candidacy for governor of Virginia next year. Trible's
triple political play, if he pulls it off, would find him moving
from six House years to six Senate years to four-and-out in
Richmond, where as governor he could not succeed himself, while the
Byrds were a half-century in a single Senate seat. Harry Flood Byrd
Jr. was appointed to the Senate by then-Gov. Albertis Harrison Jr.
in November 1965, replacing Harry Flood Byrd who had resigned,
because of illness, after serving since 1933. Harry F. Byrd Jr., as
a Democrat, was elected in 1966 to complete the rest of his
father's term, then was re-elected _ as an independent _ in 1970
and 1976. Instead of seeking re-election in 1982, Harry F. Byrd Jr.
decided to retire. Trible then won the seat, beating Democrat
Richard J. Davis, Virginia's lieutenant governor, by 33,732 votes
out of 1,415,622 cast.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
