<1ST_LINE>u p BC-APElectionService 24thadd   10-23 1197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Election Service, 24th add,1,220,1217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: 1,415,622 cast.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   30. WASHINGTON _ Republican Daniel J. Evans, of Olympia, was
born Oct. 16, 1925. Instead of running again this year, Evans is
retiring from office. He announced his decision Oct. 20, 1987.
   First elected: November 1983.
   Previously appointed: September 1983.
   Began serving: Sept. 12, 1983.
   Election history: In 1983, Evans, who had served three terms as
governor of Washington, won a special election Nov. 8 to continue
serving in the seat to which he had been appointed in September,
filling the vacancy caused by the death of Democratic Sen. Henry M.
Jackson. Evans won the special election with 55.4 percent of the
vote, defeating Democrat Michael E. Lowry, a congressman who did
not have to give up his House seat to join the Senate race. Before
coming to the Senate, Evans had been elected Washington's governor
in 1964, ousting incumbent Democrat Albert D. Rosellini, and won
re-election in 1968 and 1972. Earlier, Evans was elected to the
Washington House in 1956 and was re-elected in 1958, 1960 and 1962.
Evans was the keynote speaker at the Republican National Convention
in 1968. He was president of Evergreen State College in Olympia,
1977-83. Jackson, who had been a senator since Jan. 3, 1953, and
had won another six-year term in 1982, died Sept. 1, 1983, after a
blood vessel near his heart ruptured. Evans, coming out of
political retirement, was appointed by Republican Gov. John
Spellman to fill the vacancy, then followed up by winning the
special election to complete the term. In October 1987, citing what
he called ``fundamentally personal'' reasons, Evans announced he
was not a candidate for re-election in 1988. He spoke of his
frustrations in the Senate, the cost and length of campaigning, and
his desire to return to backpacking and mountain-climbing in
Washington state.
   
   
   31. WEST VIRGINIA _ Democrat Robert C. Byrd, of Sophia, was born
Nov. 20, 1917.
   First elected: 1958.
   Began serving: Jan. 3, 1959.
   Election history: In 1958, Byrd, after serving in the West
Virginia Legislature and three terms in the U.S. House, was elected
to the Senate with 59.2 percent of the vote, ousting incumbent
Republican Chapman Revercomb. Byrd, gaining a reputation as an
expert legislative technician, paying close attention to details,
checking and checking again, went on to re-election in 1964, 1970,
1976 and 1982, becoming a leader of the Senate's Democrats. Byrd
thus worked his way up from extreme poverty in West Virginia to
extensive power in Washington. Byrd, who was born Cornelius Calvin
Sale Jr. in North Wilkesboro, N.C., was a child when his mother
died in an influenza epidemic. His father, a furniture maker, sent
him to live with an uncle and aunt, Titus and Vlurma Byrd, on a
farm near Crab Orchard, W.Va. The farm yielded little and the elder
Byrd worked as a $2-a-day coal miner. The Byrds did not tell the
boy he was adopted until he was 16. He worked in various jobs,
including a butcher in a market. He was elected to the West
Virginia House in 1946 and re-elected in 1948. He was elected to
the West Virginia Senate in 1950. He won election to the U.S. House
in 1952 and was re-elected in 1954 and 1956.
   
   
   32. WISCONSIN _ Democrat William Proxmire, of Madison, was born
Nov. 11, 1915. Instead of running again this year, Proxmire is
retiring from office. He announced his decision Aug. 27, 1987.
   First elected: August 1957.
   Began serving: Aug. 28, 1957.
   Election history: In 1957, Proxmire, a constant campaigner since
1950 when he won a seat in Wisconsin's Legislature, was elected to
the Senate at a special election Aug. 27, gaining 56.4 percent of
the vote, to complete the term of the late Republican Joseph R.
McCarthy. Proxmire had lost three consecutive gubernatorial
elections _ in 1952, 1954 and 1956 _ before he surprisingly scored
a victory by more than 122,000 votes in the special Senate
election, defeating Republican Walter J. Kohler Jr., a former
governor; and other candidates. Proxmire had been defeated by
Kohler in the 1952 and 1954 gubernatorial elections and had lost
the 1956 governor's race to Republican Vernon W. Thomson. After
winning the Senate seat, he gained full terms in 1958, 1964, 1970,
1976 and 1982. He became nationally known as the senator who handed
out what he termed a ``golden fleece of the month,'' poking fun at
assorted projects that he considered to be a waste of the
government's money. He also was the first senator to have a hair
transplant. He was a senator who liked to run miles to and from
work. At various times, Proxmire was described as a loner, as
anti-social, and an eccentric _ and, he once said in an interview,
``all of those things are true,'' then he quickly added: ``I don't
like the term eccentric because it implies that you are off your
rocker. I call myself a pragmatic eclectic. I want to pursue the
means that are the most appropriate at the time. I don't believe in
being doctrinaire.'' In 1987, Proxmire said of the Senate: ``Where
else can you not only dream of the direction the country is going
but play a significant part in getting it there.'' He made it clear
he loved being a senator. ``We are given a chance not just to play
in the big league but to work in the biggest league of them all _
the policy-making body of the greatest country in the world. For
anyone looking for a career that offers the greatest prospect for a
fulfilling life, how can you beat it? How lucky can you get?'' In
announcing his decision to retire, he cited his age but said he was
in good health, and added: ``This is a very, very difficult
decision, believe me.''
   
   
   33. WYOMING _ Republican Malcolm Wallop, of Big Horn, was born
Feb. 27, 1933.
   First elected: 1976.
   Began serving: Jan. 3, 1977.
   Election history: In 1976, Wallop won election to the Senate
with 54.6 percent of the vote, whipping Democrat Gale W. McGee, who
had been a senator since Jan. 3, 1959. McGee, who was chairman of
what was then the Senate Post Office and Civil Service Committee,
was upset by Wallop, who at the time was a Wyoming state senator.
Wallop had made an unsuccessful bid for the 1974 Wyoming Republican
gubernatorial nomination. Out of 155,368 votes cast in the 1976
Senate race, Wallop defeated McGee by 14,252 votes and said the
voters ``put their faith in a long shot, because I represented what
they felt.'' McGee, in defeat, said: ``My record was strong and
deeply dedicated to the best interest of Wyoming and that's all you
can do. If the people decide they want to try something else,
that's what the system is all about.'' Wallop came from a family of
pioneers; his ancestors settled and ranched in Wyoming, and a
grandfather had served in both the English House of Lords and the
Wyoming Legislature. Wallop won a second term in 1982 with 56.7
percent of the vote against Democrat Rodger McDaniel, a former
state senator.
</TEXT>
