</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 0630EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-APElectionService 41stadd   10-23 2579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Election Service, 41st add,2,710,2707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-Casters And Counters,2100</HEAD>
<HEAD>200 Years And Counting: A Song of ``Electors'' And ``Tellers'' And
Such</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Election Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Votes. Votes. Votes. Officially, the way it
works, there are ``electors'' and ``tellers'' and such. Names and
numbers are everywhere. Jefferson and Burr. Lincoln and Eisenhower.
There are the ``gentlemen and gentlewomen of the Congress.'' It is
a song of the casters and the counters, a song of votes and 200
years of freedom and responsibility. It tells of when George won
'em all. George Washington, that is. Listen now. They're getting
ready to sing that song again.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CARL C. CRAFT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   And so another election will end.
   If it's close, get out your scorecard.
   If it's not, you'll soon know, unofficially, who will be the
next president.
   But either way, if you want to be nail-it-down sure who won, all
you really need is the song _ the official score _ and, please
note, that takes time. They've been singing that song, casting
those votes, counting those votes, for 200 years now.
   Whether it is a long night or a landslide in any election for
the presidency and vice presidency, it's never really over until
it's over in the Electoral College.
   And Congress officially counts the Electoral College's official
votes.
   And you can count on it. It's official, right in your
Constitution.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   It was over early in the Electoral College for George
Washington, no question about it. He was No. 1 among the electors
in his era. They cast 69 votes and he got all of them. For all we
know, they all shook his hand. They even liked him after he took
office, sang that song again and gave him all 132 at stake in the
election for the second term.
   Then again, Washington was perfect in every way. If anybody
deserved a perfect score, it had to be Washington. And you have to
figure even Sam isn't likely to play that song again quite that way
again.
   Then again, some have come close. Ronald Reagan fell only 13
electoral votes short of unanimous when the college met in 1984.
Richard Nixon was just 18 votes away from a unanimous selection in
1972. Franklin Roosevelt got 523 of the 531 at stake in 1936. And
James Monroe would have had a perfect score, but John Quincy Adams
found a friend in William Plumer of New Hampshire and the college
of 1820 marked it Monroe 231 and Adams 1.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   The Constitution demands Americans use the college to elect
their presidents and vice presidents. Many years, by the time
Congress gets around to counting what arrives from the college's
classes in 50 states and the District of Columbia, the announcement
is just for the record.
   But that doesn't stop the officials _ this is, after all, for
all time's sake.
   So, the powers of the legislative branch of government will
gather in 1989 to open the envelopes from the Electoral College,
they'll check to be sure everything is there. Then they'll count,
state by state, Alabama first.
   As they did in 1985, one of the ``tellers'' in Congress will say
the ``certificate of the electoral vote of the State of Alabama
seems to be regular in form and authentic, and it appears therefrom
that'' and then he'll say the name, and how many votes, for
president, then for vice president.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Using the Electoral College system in the Constitution,
Americans have been electing presidents and vice presidents from
Washington and John Adams, who were No. 1 and No. 2 in the first
term, to Reagan and George Bush, now No. 1 and No. 2 in the 50th
term.
   This year it is Bush for president and Dan Quayle for vice
president on the Republican ticket, and Michael Dukakis for
president and Lloyd Bentsen for vice president on the Democratic
side, and a rich assortment of other Americans wanting to serve in
the 51st term.
   And here's how we the people will decide:
   _Voters vote on Election Day Nov. 8 in 50 states and the
District of Columbia.
   They indirectly elect their next president and vice president.
   Popularly chosen electors, apportioned among the states and
Washington, D.C., are the ones who officially vote for the
candidates.
   Those electoral votes usually go to the statewide winner of the
popular vote.
   _Electors vote Dec. 17 in the states and Washington, D.C.,
sending results to Washington.
   _Congress, in joint session Jan. 6, opens the envelopes, counts
the electoral votes for president and for vice president, and
announces the winners to the world.
   _The newly elected president and vice president take office Jan.
20.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   The Electoral College system was new when George Washington
first heard the official word.
   Here's how that first race turned out:
   Connecticut, casts 7 electoral votes for Washington. Delaware, 3
for Washington. Georgia, 5 for Washington. Maryland, 6 for
Washington. Massachusetts, 10 for Washington. New Hampshire, 5 for
Washington. New Jersey, 6 for Washington. Pennsylvania, 10 for
Washington. South Carolina, 7 for Washington. Virginia, 10 for
Washington. Everybody accounted for? There's a deadlock in New
York, so they won't be here. Rhode Island and North Carolina are
not here, either, but they haven't ratified the Constitution yet.
   Total: 69 electoral votes for Washington. He is unanimously
elected president of the United States.
   As was the rule in the early elections, next in the tally gets
the vice presidency. That was John Adams, at 34 votes. We've got
some also-rans here, but nobody is close to Adams. John Jay's got
9. Robert H. Harrison and John Rutledge are here at a tie with 6
for Bob and 6 for John. Four go for John Hancock. George Clinton
picked up three. A couple here and there for some others.
   But, all agree, Washington was one of a kind.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   As the years went on, the operation of the college was put to
the test, people argued over whether a direct election would be
better than this indirect system. Defenders said this thing works,
leave it alone; opponents said it needed fixing and fast.
   Controversy centered on how the electoral vote math and the
total popular vote math sometimes didn't match, with a close
election in the popular vote turning into a landslide in the
Electoral College because, big state or small state, the general
rule is that the winner takes all of that state.
   States with more people get more electoral votes. But each
state, no matter how many people live there, casts at least three
electoral votes. Wyoming is as strong in the college as the
District of Columbia. Alaska gets what Vermont gets.
   And the mixture changes every decade, in big ways and small,
based on the census. This is a nation with wheels and wings, a
people wanting more sun, perhaps, or another job, perhaps, or just
another place down that road.
   The government is required to count where you are every 10
years, and it hands out House seats based on those census figures.
But the Senate seats are fixed _ two to a state, be it big state or
small.
   All of that is put into the electoral vote system.
   So, as it stands now, California is the current heavyweight,
with 47 electoral votes _ because it has two senators, just like
the other 49 states, but it also has 45 members of the House, and
no state can match that.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Early on, they changed one of the voting rules when trouble
developed. It came in the balloting for a president and vice
president for the fourth term, 1801-05.
   Again, as they had done in 1789, 1792 and 1796, electors voted
for two candidates. The one with the most votes became president,
next in line got the next job down.
   This time, it's a tie for the top job: 73 votes for Thomas
Jefferson, 73 votes for Aaron Burr.
   The House had to settle it. In the end, Jefferson won. For the
future, to keep this sort of thing from happening again, the
Constitution is amended. Separate balloting for president and vice
president from now on.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Down through time, while others argued that it works or it
doesn't work or it just might not work when we need it the most,
the electors, on schedule, did their number, did it and didn't do
it again for another four years.
   Some of them did it their own way _ they are, after all, free
agents _ but most remained with the program as written. The
colleges of Washington's day and of Jefferson's day, too, passed
away, one by one, replaced by others, one by one.
   And, through the years, the official singers continued their
song, officially revealing results, even when the word already was
out.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Abraham Lincoln's name was heard just before war, and again just
before the end of war. Then is never heard again. Sadness in that
silence. Franklin Roosevelt's name was heard four times, once when
he left Alfred M. Landon with only Vermont to go with Maine. Then
Harry Truman's name is heard when he surprised those who were
certain it would never be. Twice came Dwight Eisenhower, Richard
Nixon, Ronald Reagan, just as twice had come Ulysses S. Grant,
William McKinley, Woodrow Wilson.
   The Virginians with the famous names _ Washington, Jefferson,
James Madison, James Monroe _ dominated the early going when this
compromise creation was being brought up and running, but then came
Tennessee's Andrew Jackson, and then Illinois gave both Lincoln and
Lincoln's general, Grant.
   Ohio's field included Rutherford B. Hayes who survived one of
the biggest disputes of all by topping New York's Samuel J. Tilden,
185-184. New York's luck was mixed, with Grover Cleveland swinging
in and out and in again, followed by Franklin Roosevelt's four big
showings in a row.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   In 1985, just before Congress opened, counted and announced the
results of Reagan's re-election landslide, old news at that point,
Rep. Jim Wright, D-Texas, who became the House speaker, called the
Electoral College ``a relic of the powdered wig and snuff box era.
It's a charming exercise ... (but) I think it's outlived its
usefulness.''
   But, like it or not, until America settles on something else,
the Electoral College is official voter. And it is the official
vote that counts.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   And, how does this official election music sound as the
officials play it for the ages?
   When last we heard Reagan's name, for example, the action was
Jan. 7, 1985. As the Congressional Record so officially records it,
even as it capitalizes it, for all time:
   
   ``At 12 o'clock and 55 minutes p.m., the Doorkeeper, the
Honorable James T. Molloy, announced the Vice President and the
Senate of the United States.
   ``The Senate entered the Hall of the House of Representatives,
headed by the Vice President and the Secretary of the Senate, the
Members and officers of the House rising to receive them.
   ``The Vice President took his seat as the Presiding Officer of
the joint onvention of the two Houses, the Speaker pro tempore (Mr.
WRIGHT) of the House occupying the chair on his left.
   ``The joint session was called to order by the Vice President.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Many of the words that follow in quotes sound strange indeed.
But these words flow from tradition and the law, like the sound of
people singing just as their parents sang, sounding the same
through time, singing the joys of their freedom for all the world
to hear, exercising their vote and the power and the responsibility
it brings. The names, the numbers, they change in time. You're
hearing it now, but you could be hearing it then when the names
Lincoln, Wilson, Roosevelt, Eisenhower would ring where Reagan
rings now.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   To continue:
   ``The VICE PRESIDENT. Mr. Speaker, Members of the Congress, the
Senate and the House of Representatives, pursuant to the
requirements of the Constitution and the laws of the United States,
have met in joint session for the purpose of opening the
certificates and ascertaining and counting the votes of the
electors of the several States for President and Vice President.
   ``Under the precedents, unless a motion shall be made in any
case, the reading of the formal portions of the certificates will
be dispensed with after ascertainment has been made that the
certificates are authentic and correct in form, the tellers will
count and make a list of the votes cast by the electors of the
several States.''
   
   So it began, the counting went forward.
   
   ``Mr. ANNUNZIO (one of the tellers): Mr. President, the
certificate of the electoral vote of the State of Alabama seems to
be regular in form and authentic, and it appears therefrom that
Ronald Reagan of the State of California received nine votes for
President, and George Bush of the State of Texas received nine
votes for vice president.''
   
   As the counting continued, it was noted:
   
   ``The tellers then proceeded to read, count, and announce, as
was done in the case of the State of Alabama, the electoral votes
of the several States in alphabetical order.''
   
   Next order of business:
   
   ``The VICE PRESIDENT. Gentlemen and gentlewomen of the Congress,
the certificates of all of the States have now been opened and read
and the tellers will make the final ascertainment of the results
and deliver the same to the President of the Senate.''
   
   That was done.
   
   At last, the final words:
   
   ``The VICE PRESIDENT. The state of the vote for President of the
United States, as delivered to the President of the Senate, is as
follows:
   ``The whole number of the electors appointed to vote for
President of the United States is 538, of which a majority is 270.
   ``Ronald Reagan, of the State of California, has received for
President of the United States 525 votes.
   ``Walter Mondale, of the State of Minnesota, has received 13
votes.
   ``The state of the vote for Vice President of the United States,
as delivered to the President of the Senate, is as follows:
   ``The whole number of the electors appointed to vote for Vice
President of the United States is 538, of which a majority is 270.
   ``George Bush, of the State of Texas, has received for vice
president of the United States 525 votes.
   ``Geraldine A. Ferraro, of the State of New York, has received
13 votes.
   ``This announcement of the state of the vote by the President of
the Senate shall be deemed a sufficient declaration of the persons
elected President and Vice President of the United States, each for
the term beginning on the 20th day of January 1985, and shall be
entered, together with a list of the votes, on the Journals of the
Senate and the House of Representatives.
   ``The purposes for which the joint session of the two Houses of
Congress has been called, pursuant to Senate Concurrent Resolution
1, 99th Congress, having been accomplished, the Chair declares the
joint session dissolved.''
   
   The final words thus spoken, the record notes for history the
time they are spoken.
   
   ``(Thereupon, at 1 o'clock and 22 minutes p.m., the joint
session of the two Houses of Congress was dissolved.)''
   
   Until we meet again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
