<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Election Service, 42nd add,480,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-And The Winners Were</HEAD>
<HEAD>All The Presidents' Figures: Electoral Votes, From A. Lincoln to
Z. Taylor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Election Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Table and footnotes are in agate</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CARL C. CRAFT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   With two Lone Stars on the national tickets this year, no one
knows whether Texas will be carried by Sen. Lloyd Bentsen and his
Democratic partner Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts or by Vice
President George Bush and his GOP sidekick Dan Quayle of Indiana.
   And, just as certainly, Texans had no idea back in U.S. Grant's
day that the winning U.S. senator from Massachusetts they voted
against in the vice presidential race would someday turn out to be
Texan Bentsen's great-great-uncle.
   Indiana, certainly, has no complaint about the Texas treatment.
Texas did vote back then for a Hoosier for president. He didn't get
that top job that time but he later won the next job down.
   You remember Henry Wilson and Thomas A. Hendricks, vice
presidents of the United States.
   It turns out Wilson also was vice presidential nominee Bentsen's
distant relative from Massachusetts, now the home of Dukakis,
presidential half of the Democratic ticket this year.
   Hendricks, from Indiana, eventually became quite a name in the
households of his day.
   Texans went for B. Gratz Brown of Missouri over Wilson in 1872.
But they were outnumbered, so Wilson won the vice presidency and
Brown got honorable mention.
   Horace Greeley of New York was Republican Grant's real rival in
the election that year. Greeley and Brown were the ticket for some
Republicans unhappy with the way Grant was minding the store, and
also for the Democrats. However, after the election, Greeley died,
and his presidential electoral votes were cast for assorted other
candidates.
   Brown turned out to get electoral votes for both for president
(18) and for vice president (47). Hendricks collected 42 for
president.
   Grant won the presidential election with 286 votes, and Wilson
got the same for vice president. Indiana contributed 15 of those
votes to the winning ticket. Texas cast 8 votes for Hendricks for
president and 8 for Brown for vice president.
   Hendricks finished second to Grant that year but came back in
1884 to win the vice presidency under Grover Cleveland.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Through 200 years of America's election experience, the
candidates appear once or arrive again, asking to enter the line of
leaders. The presidents emerge, from A. Lincoln to Z. Taylor, and
the vice presidents, too. In time, some are remembered only in
archives; others survive across the ages and are still on the money.
   From the ranks of the people, the people elect their presidents
and vice presidents on schedule every four years, giving the
winners the executive keys to keep until the next winners arrive.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
