<HEAD>BC-Presidential Candidates, 3 Takes</HEAD>
<HEAD>At The Top: Fulani Among Others In Presidential Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Election Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Table of selected candidates and full state-by-state list are
in agate</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAMELA B. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidate Lenora B. Fulani will be atop America's
ballots on Election Day along with Republican George Bush and
Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   Many voters will have various other options.
   According to a ballot-access count Sept. 26 by the Federal
Election Commission and latest tallies by the ballot-watching News
Election Service, at least 17 independent or other-party
presidential candidates are to be on ballots in one or more states.
   Fulani of New York will join Bush of Texas and Dukakis of
Massachusetts on the Nov. 8 ballots around the nation, while Ronald
E. Paul of Texas will be on most ballots.
   Elsewhere, depending on the state, voters will find Lyndon H.
LaRouche Jr., Willa Kenoyer and Eugene J. McCarthy among others
running as either independents or other-party candidates for the
presidency.
   Fulani, a psychologist who worked to become the first black
female presidential candidate to show on ballots throughout the
nation, is running as the candidate of the New Alliance Party which
bills itself as ``the party of the rainbow.''
   In some states, she will be listed as an independent or the
candidate of the Illinois Solidarity, Alliance or United Citizens
parties.
   She says she hopes to draw enough votes from Dukakis to make the
Democratic Party take notice, adding: ``What I am schooling people
to do is to use our votes in a way that puts pressure on the
party'' which ``needs us to get elected. I want us to have power.''
   Fulani failed in her attempt to unseat New York Gov. Mario Cuomo
in 1986.
   Paul, a native of Pittsburgh, Pa., and a fiscal conservative who
was elected four times as a Republican to the U.S. House
representing a congressional district in Texas, is the Libertarian
Party's presidential nominee this time. He is listed as an
independent in some states.
   In 1984, Libertarian David Bergland finished in third place in
the presidential race, drawing 227,204 votes nationally when
Republican Ronald Reagan defeated Democrat Walter Mondale.
   ``I changed parties last year because I felt the voters deserve
a choice,'' says Paul. ``I left the GOP because it has lost all
credibility on balancing the budget.''
   ``I would abolish the Federal Reserve,'' Paul says, and ``create
a sound money system'' and ``I'd get rid of the income tax. It's
only a new 20th century phenomenon in order to finance the welfare
workers state.
   ``Let's say we did not police the world and we had no welfare.
Would we need an income tax? Isn't it interesting that the income
tax came about the time we changed our foreign policy and got a
central bank and started fighting wars overseas? In Woodrow
Wilson's day.''
   McCarthy, a Watkins, Minn., native who resides in rural
Woodville, Va., served a decade in the U.S. House and a pair of
six-year terms in the U.S. Senate from Minnesota as a Democrat. Now
he is in his fourth presidential campaign.
   He failed to win the Democratic presidential nomination in 1968
and 1972. In 1976, against winning Democrat Jimmy Carter and losing
Republican Gerald R. Ford, McCarthy ran as an independent candidate
for the White House and received 680,390 of the 81,603,346 votes
cast.
   ``There is no real choice between Democrats and Republicans,''
McCarthy said in announcing his 1988 bid. ``If any new direction is
to come, it must come through an independent party, the Consumer
Party, and I have willingly offered myself to lead it.''
   He also will appear on ballots as an independent or a Minnesota
Progressive candidate.
   It was in the 1968 presidential race that McCarthy became a folk
hero among the young when he was the political maverick whose
opposition to the Vietnam War helped mark the beginning of the end
of that conflict.
   ``Sure, I've lost before, but I didn't feel I wasted my time,
and I expect to have a significant impact,'' McCarthy says. ``This
year the one thing we have to do is shake up the two-party system,
and that's what I hope to do.''
   LaRouche, of Virginia, is running this year as an independent or
the candidate of the National Economic Recovery Party or the
Democrats for Economic Recovery Party.
   In unsuccessful bids, LaRouche was the 1976 presidential
candidate of the U.S. Labor Party which he founded in 1973; he
announced as his party's 1980 candidate in January 1979 but that
September he decided to run as a Democratic candidate in 1980; he
again sought the Democratic nomination in 1984 and 1988; and he ran
as an independent in the 1984 election.
   Kenoyer, a free-lance writer from Shelby, Mich., is campaigning
as a Socialist and will appear in some states as the Liberty Union
or independent candidate.
   ``I learned my socialism on my daddy's knee back in the
mid-1930s,'' she says; her father was a labor activist.
   Kenoyer says she would spend her first hour in the White House
dismantling the CIA and ``the second hour, the FBI goes.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
