<HEAD>BC-Blacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dawkins and Keyes Trying To Follow Brooke's Path To Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Election Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAMELA B. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Black Republicans Maurice A. Dawkins of Arlington, Va. and Alan
L. Keyes of Rockville, Md., taking on prominent Democrats, are
trying to follow Edward William Brooke's path to the United States
Senate.
   Brooke, a Massachusetts Republican, was the first black U.S.
senator since the nation's Reconstruction after the Civil War, and
only the third black in the Senate _ all of them Republicans _ in
American history.
   Elected in 1966, Brooke began serving Jan. 3, 1967, as the first
black in the Senate since 1881.
   This year, Dawkins, a businessman, is running against Democratic
former Gov. Charles S. Robb of Virginia for the Senate seat being
given up by Republican Paul S. Trible, who is retiring, while Keyes
is attempting to unseat Democratic Sen. Paul S. Sarbanes.
   After winning the GOP nomination, Dawkins declared that ``they
said it couldn't be done, but we did it. They say Chuck Robb can't
be beaten, but we're going to beat him.''
   In April, Dawkins, heading the state GOP's minority outreach
program, said black voters could gain greater political power by
increasing their participation in the Republican Party, and he said
the Democrats had taken black support for granted.
   Keyes, a former assistant U.S. secretary of state, was selected
in June by Maryland GOP leaders as their party's Senate candidate
replacing Thomas L. Blair who had been nominated at the March
primary but later dropped out of the competition.
   Keyes pledged to carry a message that ``freedom works.''
   Brooke won re-election in 1972 and lost his 1978 bid for a third
term, leaving office in January 1979.
   Two blacks went to the Senate after the Civil War, having been
elected by the Mississippi Legislature.
   The first black senator _ and first black member of Congress _
was Hiram Rhodes Revels of Mississippi, who served after the state
was readmitted to representation in Congress in 1870. He took his
seat in February 1870 and served for a term expiring March 3, 1871.
   The first black to serve a full six-year term in the Senate was
Blanche Kelso Bruce of Mississippi, who held office from march 4,
1875, to March 3, 1881.
   There were 22 black voting members of the U.S. House during the
100th Congress, all of them Democrats. All are running this year
for new terms.
   State by state, they were:
   _ California (4): Ronald V. Dellums, Julian Carey Dixon,
Augustus F. Hawkins and Mervyn M. Dymally.
   _ Georgia (1): John R. Lewis.
   _ Illinois (3): Charles Arthur Hayes, Gus Savage and Cardiss
Robertson Collins.
   _ Maryland (1): Kweisi Mfume.
   _ Michigan (2): John Conyers Jr. and George W. Crockett Jr.
   _ Mississippi (1): A. Michael Espy.
   _ Missouri (2): William L. Clay and Alan D. Wheat.
   _ New York (4): Floyd H. Flake, Edolphus Towns, Major Robert
Odell Owens and Charles B. Rangel.
   _ Ohio (1): Louis Stokes.
   _ Pennsylvania (1): William H. Gray III.
   _ Tennessee (1): Harold E. Ford.
   _ Texas (1): Mickey Leland.
   In all, throughout U.S. history, 59 blacks have been elected
from the states and served in the House.
   State by state, the totals:
   _ 10 from Illinois.
   _ 8 from South Carolina.
   _ 7 from New York.
   _ 5 from California.
   _ 4 from North Carolina.
   _ 3 from Alabama, 3 from Georgia, 3 from Michigan.
   _ 2 from Maryland, 2 from Mississippi, 2 from Missouri, 2 from
Pennsylvania, 2 from Texas.
   _ 1 from Florida, 1 from Indiana, 1 from Louisiana, 1 from Ohio,
1 from Tennessee, 1 from Virginia.
   The first black who was elected and served in the House was Rep.
Joseph Hayne Rainey of South Carolina, a Republican. He was elected
in 1870 to fill a vacancy in the 41st Congress, and he was
re-elected to the 42nd, 43rd, 44th and 45th Congresses, serving in
the House from Dec. 12, 1870, to March 3, 1879.
   There are no blacks among the nation's 50 state governors.
Although no black has been elected governor, a black lieutenant
governor _ Pinckney B. S. Pinchback _ briefly served as Louisiana's
acting governor in 1872-73 after the governor was impeached.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-VodkaAds Bjt   10-23 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vodka Ads, Bjt,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shake But Don't Drink the Absolut Vodka Ad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Absolut Vodka marketers want you to shake up
their new magazine advertisement. But, please, don't try to drink
it.
   Just in time for Christmas, U.S. distributors of the drink from
Sweden have come up a new twist that introduces some motion to
print advertising.
   The ads, designed to simulate a snowstorm, have see-through
plastic pressing a clear liquid tight against a black page that
carries an illustration of an Absolut Vodka bottle draped with a
red scarf.
   When the page is shaken, white flecks of plastic float through
the liquid to make it look like it's snowing around the bottle.
   Carillon Importers Ltd., based in Teaneck, N.J., and the sole
U.S. distributor of Absolut Vodka, spent in excess of $1 million to
produce the ads and buy space to run them in three magazines _ New
York, L.A. Style and the liquor trade publication Market Watch. It
hopes 2 million people will see them.
   The ``Absolut Wonderland'' ads are the latest step in marketers'
efforts to cut through commercial clutter and get people to pay
attention to a message.
   Advertisers selling everything from cookies and perfume to
liqueurs and Rolls-Royce automobiles have used scent strips in
magazine ads. Readers have faced cardboard pop-ups of Stetson hats,
Christmas stockings stuffed with a paper bottle and views of the
San Francisco skyline in their magazines.
   Toyota Motor Sales in USA put a cardboard 3-D viewfinder in a
magazine ad last year so readers could glimpse its new Corolla
model. Sellers of Johnnie Walker Black Label Scotch put a dozen
peel-and-stick labels in a two-page ad last year so readers could
remind others of what they wanted for Christmas.
   Carillon was one of two liquor distributors last year that
placed microchips in the middle of magazine spreads that played
Christmas carols when the page was cracked open.
   ``At Christmastime, magazines are crowded with ads. To catch the
reader's attention, you have to do something a step ahead of the
others,'' said Michel Roux, president and chief executive of
Carillon.
   One complaint about the musical ads last year was that some
people couldn't get the music to stop. Music reportedly played
incessantly in some apartment building lobbies after certain
magazines were stuffed in the mailboxes.
   Carillon and its admakers at TBWA Advertising Inc. say they have
taken every precaution this year to avoid one potential complaint _
soggy magazines.
   ``We can't say it will never break,'' TBWA president Richard
Costello said. ``If somebody sticks it with a knife, they may
puncture it.''
   But he said the ads were rigorously tested for leakage, and
proved tough.
   Costello said there were unique problems in preparing the ads.
The flakes had to be exactly the right size so they wouldn't stick
together. A small amount of antifreeze was added to the liquid so
it wouldn't freeze and crack if the magazines were stored at low
temperatures.
   And, oh yes, the ad itself notes that the liquid is not Absolut
vodka. It is a non-toxic liquid ``not for human consumption,'' the
ad says.
   Edward Kosner, editor and publisher of New York magazine, said
he thinks imaginative advertising approaches are usually good for
the advertiser, the magazine that runs them and the magazine
business in general.
   ``I don't think you could run a novelty unit like this every
week, because people might find it obtrusive,'' he said. ``But
running one occasionally sparks up the magazine and attracts
attention to the advertising.''
   Costello has no complaints. He said Absolut Vodka sales were up
35 percent last year, and are running 33 percent higher so far this
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1505EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ConceptCars     10-23 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Concept Cars,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>From the Drawing Board to the Highway</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was not too long ago that automobile designers
watched their drawings come alive in one car _ and then vanish into
automotive lore.
   But the ``concept'' or ``show'' car that was a designer's pipe
dream yesterday might actually make it to the road someday, auto
executives say.
   ``The idea of show cars is to test the limits,'' said Tom Gale,
Chrysler Motors Corp.'s vice president for product design.
   ``We're living in a world that's four to five years in the
future,'' he said.
   Yet today, ``There are several reasons why the concept cars look
a lot more realistic,'' said Jerry Palmer, director of advanced
design at General Motors Corp. ``A lot of it has to do with
technology.''
   ``The cars in the '50s were really wild-looking things. You
couldn't do those kinds of things in production,'' he said.
``Forget about the fact that they may or not have had fins; they
had glass canopies. At that time the hardware and the technology
wasn't there.
   ``Now, all the technology is available. It's kind of hard to do
a wild show car and shock anyone anymore. Someone is going to ask
`Why can't I have one?'''
   The car buyer can, bit by bit.
   Gone are the bullet-like looks of the '50s and '60s when
designers let their imagination roam unfettered by manufacturing or
engineering restraints. Here are more aerodynamic lines, with
smoother unions between metal and glass.
   ``In the '50s, it was a period of incredible optimism,'' said
Dave Turner, director of advanced concept design at Ford Motor Co.
``I think in the '60s and '70s, society in general began to take a
little more pragmatic approach.''
   Concept cars today, he said, ``are used to condition ourselves
to some ideas and test people's reactions.''
   That's where the auto shows come in. Every year, automakers haul
some of their design cars around the country and the world to show
them off.
   Gale said the Chrysler Portofino concept car, with four doors
that swing open on pivots and close like guillotines, is getting
``show worn.''
   Nowadays, with a little imagination, show goers can nearly see
themselves tooling down the highway in one of the concept cars. But
people's imagination had to be particularly fertile to picture
themselves behind the wheel of a concept car from the '50s or early
'60s, complete with their canopies.
   Despite all the other changes through the years, glass roofs
have endured. Most of the show cars automakers are willing to
exhibit have clear roofs.
   And the problem that faced designers of yesteryear _ incredible
heat buildup in the canopy _ is disappearing with the advent of
films that can darken as sunlight gets brighter. It's the sort of
stuff that's been used in eyeglasses that turn lenses dark outside
and clear inside.
   That glass technology is one example of how designers' hands are
being freed by science.
   And part of that science is creeping into cars on the highways.
Automakers are installing such light-sensitive films in mirrors on
some of their models.
   ``These are vehicles that aren't that far away from reality
because they are designed or engineered around technology available
now,'' Palmer said.
   Along with changes in technology in the cars and the factories,
the car buyer also is influencing the designers.
   ``The customer has gotten very sophisticated,'' Turner said.
``You can't fool him anymore. He demands that real technological
improvement.''
   ``They don't want technology for its own sake, they want
technology they can believe in.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
