<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-88 1510EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-StationBreaks     10-23 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Station Breaks,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitsubishi Offers $12 Million in San Francisco Graffiti Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mitsubishi has a new idea that gives new
meaning to the phrase ``station break.''
   The Japanese company has offered city officials $12 million to
battle graffiti if the electronics company wins exclusive rights to
install television screens displaying news and commercials in
underground transit stations.
   Mitsubishi has tentatively planned to design and install the
prototype system at its own expense and to maintain them in the
city's stations for the next eight years. A local firm, Visualmedia
Concepts, would sell advertising for the color TV monitors.
   San Francisco's Municipal Railway, which has underground
stations along Market Street, would receive a small portion of the
advertising revenue.
   The televisions could also be used to announce train arrivals
and departures, to display public service messages and give news
reports.
   Jaimie Levin, the railway's director of community relations,
called the proposal ``very speculative.''
   ``We don't know if they can give us what we want,'' she said
Friday. ``We may not be able to go this route with them, but we'd
be fools if we didn't explore it.''
   Televisions that display advertising logos, but not action
videos, already have been placed in subway stations in Chicago.
   The municipal railway's general manager, Bill Stead, recently
proposed an anti-graffiti program that would cost up to $13 million
annualy, but Mayor Art Agnos said a fare increase could not be used
to pay for it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
