<HEAD>UAW Approves New Chrysler Contract; Members Go Back To Work Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FENTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers members at the Chrysler
Corp. minivan assembly plant here were scheduled to return to work
Monday after voting to end a two-week-old strike.
   Union members at Chrysler's plant No. 2 ratified a new local
contract Friday by a 70 percent majority, with 1,677 voting in
favor of the agreement and 707 voting against it.
   Negotiators for the UAW and Chrysler reached the tentative
agreement on Thursday.
   The strike began Oct. 5 when some 3,200 union members walked off
their jobs after negotiators failed to meet a contract deadline. A
tentative agreement was reached two days later, but it was rejected
in two ratification votes.
   Chrysler filed suit last week seeking a temporary injunction to
halt the walkout, but U.S. District Judge Clyde Cahill went no
further than to urge the two parties to settle their differences.
   Karen Stewart, a spokeswoman for Chrysler, said the strike cost
the company an estimated $3 million a day.
   She said Chrysler, as part of the tentative accord reached
Thursday, would drop its suit against the local.
