<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru   10-23 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC, 1st Ld-Writethru,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Ministers Agree to Freeze Production at Current Levels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout with Algerian minister's comments. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC members who ended three days of talks
over the weekend agreed the cartel should maintain its crude oil
output at current levels and not increase it until the group
reaches a new agreement on production, the oil minister of Algeria
said Sunday.
   OPEC leaders said several production plans were under
consideration.
   The Algerian representative, Balkacem Nabi, said some of the
eight ministers at last week's meeting asked several OPEC members
to reduce their output but were refused.
   The ministers then agreed to freeze the cartel's output at its
current levels of around 21 million barrels a day, he said.
   The pricing and long-term strategy committees of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries had met in hopes of
making progress toward a new production agreement that might
stabilize prices.
   Rampant overproduction by several OPEC members forced the price
of oil to about $12 a barrel recently. The cartel's output is well
above its agreed-upon overall ceiling of 15.06 million barrels a
day for 12 of the 13 member nations. OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman
said Saturday the ministers decided to propose a 17.5
million-barrel-a-day ceiling on production, up from the current
15.06 million.
   However, Secretary-General Subroto of Indonesia told a later
news conference several production plans were under consideration.
He said no one plan had met the approval of all eight ministers.
   Lukman, who also is Nigeria's oil minister, said the proposed
ceiling of 17.5 million would be for the short term with an
unspecified increase later.
   Nabi said seven of the ministers said they were more concerned
with revenue than production.
   OPEC experts have estimated the demand for the cartel's crude
output in the final quarter of the year to be 18.9 to 19.3 million
barrels a day, which means the current glut of crude on world
markets will continue.
   In a statement released after the talks ended, the cartel said
its price planners would meet again in Vienna, Austria, on Nov. 17
after consultations with their governments.
   A full ministerial conference is set for Nov. 21 in Vienna.
   Lukman told reporters he was happy with the latest meetings. He
said all eight participating ministers had emphasized the need for
Iraq to come back into the quota agreement.
   However, Iran resisted at the meeting any proposal that would
give Iraq production parity with Iran.
   The meeting's chief objective was to secure a new production
control pact to include Iraq for the first time since 1986. Iraq
has refused to abide by any OPEC-mandated production quota if it
does not have parity with Iran.
   Iran has an OPEC quota of 2.4 million barrels a day and Iraq's
official ceiling is 1.5 million barrels a day. The two countries
have been at war since September 1980 but are now recognizing a
cease-fire.
   The countries represented at the meetings, besides Iran and
Iraq, were Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Indonesia, Algeria, Venezuela and
Nigeria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881023-0113 </DOCNO>
