<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Bush-SmallBusiness     10-23 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Small Business,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Business Executives Prefer Bush, Survey Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush was the overwhelming choice for
president among a survey of presidents of small businesses released
Sunday.
   In the survey, published in the magazine D&B Reports, 63 percent
of the respondents said they planned to vote for the Republican
presidential nominee, while 14 percent said they would vote for
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis. Twenty-three percent said they
were undecided.
   The survey, to be printed in the November-December issue of the
magazine published by Dun & Bradstreet Corp., also found small
business presidents upbeat about the direction their companies and
the economy will take next year.
   Seventy-one percent of the respondents called themselves
optimistic, while 14 percent said they were pessimistic about
prospects for 1989.
   The survey was mailed to presidents and owners of 5,000
businesses with annual sales under $12 million. Dun & Bradstreet
said the companies were selected randomly from its database of more
than 9 million businesses.
   The response rate was 12 percent, Dun & Bradstreet said.
</TEXT>
