<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Pohlad'sBanks     10-23 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pohlad's Banks,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assistance Request Leads To New Bidding On Two Texas Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have reopened bidding for the
purchase of Texas American Bancshares Inc. and National Bancshares
Corp., paving the way for bidders who previously submitted
proposals to step back into the action.
   Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. officials said Friday Minnesota
businessman Carl Pohlad's request for more federal assistance in
his plan to buy the two banks was too significant to approve
without obtaining competing offers.
   Pohlad, owner of the Minnesota Twins, said in July he would put
up $200 million in capital to go with $475 million in government
aid to buy Fort Worth-based Texas American and San Antonio-based
National Bancshares.
   But after a close review of the companies' books, Pohlad tried
to make changes in the proposed transaction.
   Texas American chairman Joseph Grant told the Dallas Morning
News Pohlad was expected to join in the new round of bidding.
   Other likely contenders are Richard Rainwater of Fort Worth,
former financial adviser to the billionaire Bass brothers, and
Morton Meyerson of Dallas. The two previously submitted a joint
proposal to buy the banking firms.
   Also a likely suitor in the new bidding is Dallas banker Gerald
Ford.
   Rainwater, contacted Sunday by The Associated Press, would not
say whether he would re-enter the bidding for Texas American and
National Bancshares and declined to comment on the transaction.
   Morton and Ford did not return telephone calls Sunday from The
Associated Press.
   Pohlad's Minneapolis firms, MEI Diversified Inc. and Bank Shares
Inc., have been trying to acquire Texas American and National
Bancshares.
   Speculation was the deal soured when disagreement was fueled by
generous terms subsequently granted NCNB Corp. of Charlotte, N.C.,
to take over First RepublicBank Corp. of Dallas.
   Although the FDIC will finance possible future losses at First
Republic, Pohlad would get no further help if losses exceeded $475
million.
   If Pohlad's transaction goes through, his companies would own
the fourth-largest banking company in Texas. Its $8 billion in
assets would dwarf Bank Shares' present assets of $1.8 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
