<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's 38.4 million Social Security
recipients can count on a 4 percent increase in their benefits
starting next January that will boost the average retired worker's
pension by $21 a month, the government announced.
   The increase announced Friday, the second-largest in 6{ years,
will mean the typical benefit payment will go from $516 to $537 per
month.
   Offsetting the good news on benefit increases was a $7.10 hike
in Medicare premiums, which will rise to $31.90 a month starting in
January. They are deducted directly from the monthly benefits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Older consumers, who control about $900 billion
of the country's wealth, are unhappy with how they are portrayed by
U.S. advertisers and don't mind squawking about it, according to a
researcher.
   George P. Moschis has categorized the over-55's into ``healthy
hermits,'' ``ailing outgoers,'' ``frail recluses'' and ``healthy
indulgers.''
   He surveyed 1,000 people aged 55 and older and found 82 percent
of them believe the products they buy don't work as promised and 75
percent of those who are unhappy make it a point to let others know
their feelings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge awarded nearly $3 million to 766
blacks and women who were discriminated against by the Mississippi
Employment Service office in Cleveland.
   Some of the plaintiffs in the 1972 racial and sexual
discrimination suit will receive up to $40,000 if Friday's decision
stands.
   However, the employment office will appeal to the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans, arguing against the
formula used to compute the awards.
</TEXT>
