<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0531</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department issued regulations
barring most private employers from using polygraph or lie detector
tests to screen job applicants and greatly restricting use of the
devices to test present employees.
   The regulations issued Friday, which take effect Dec. 27,
implement legislation outlawing about 85 percent of the current use
of polygraph examinations and voice stress analyzers.
   The congressional Office of Technology Assessment estimated 2
million polygraph examinations were conducted last year _ 90
percent of them by private employers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Inc. plans to lease or buy
around 60 new aircraft to upgrade its aging fleet, the airline's
general counsel said.
   The new narrow-body planes would cost TWA a total of up to $1.5
billion, Mark A. Buckstein said Friday.
   He said TWA's board of directors approved the action in
principle in the early summer, and that the airline has started
negotiations with three major aircraft manufacturers and a number
of leasing companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump says he plans to spend
``tremendous amounts of money'' to upgrade Eastern Airlines'
shuttle service after he takes over as its new owner.
   Trump agreed on Oct. 12 to purchase the profitable Northeast
shuttle from Texas Air Corp. for $365 million in cash.
   The interiors of the 17 Boeing 727s will be completely redone,
safety will be stressed and the shuttle's airport terminals in New
York, Boston and Washington will be refurbished, Trump said Friday
in a telephone interview.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Northwest lawmakers urged the Japanese
ambassador to the United States to help revive talks aimed at
eliminating Japanese trade barriers to U.S. timber products.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., and Rep. Sid Morrison, R-Wash., said
Friday in a letter to Ambassador Nobuo Matsunaga the United States
had expected the talks would resume after Secretary of State George
Shultz and the Japanese foreign minister signed an agreement in
1986.
   The Reagan administration has been pressing for new talks since
August.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW PALTZ, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disapproval expressed by International
Business Machines Corp. over Big Blue wine has prompted winemaker
Jack Ransom to scale down his marketing plans.
   Ransom began last summer bottling wines at his Chateau Georges
winery under the Big Blue label. The wine was promoted as the wine
of choice for an international organization of former IBM employees
called Big Blue.
   But IBM in September voiced concern over possible trademark
infringement because the company manufactures a typewriter ribbon
called Big Blue.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward Friday, pushing the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials up 2.31 to 2,183.50 and a new 1988 high.
   Bond prices fell, with the 30-year Treasury bond losing about $5
for every $1,000 in face value while its yield rose toward 8.9
percent.
   The dollar finished mostly lower in busy foreign-exchange
trading.
   Precious metals futures prices fell sharply, while cattle
futures were lower, pork futures were mixed and grains and soybeans
posted moderate losses.
</TEXT>
